</div></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-below"><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1011085734">.mw-parser-output .reflist{font-size:90%;margin-bottom:0.5em;list-style-type:decimal}.mw-parser-output .reflist .references{font-size:100%;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:inherit}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns-2{column-width:30em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns-3{column-width:25em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns{margin-top:0.3em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns ol{margin-top:0}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns li{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .reflist-upper-alpha{list-style-type:upper-alpha}.mw-parser-output .reflist-upper-roman{list-style-type:upper-roman}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-alpha{list-style-type:lower-alpha}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-greek{list-style-type:lower-greek}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-roman{list-style-type:lower-roman}</style><div class="reflist">
</div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Mars</b> is the fourth <a href="/wiki/Planet" title="Planet">planet</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Sun" title="Sun">Sun</a> and the second-smallest planet in the <a href="/wiki/Solar_System" title="Solar System">Solar System</a>, larger only than <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(planet)" title="Mercury (planet)">Mercury</a>. In the <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English language</a>, Mars is named for the <a href="/wiki/Mars_(mythology)" title="Mars (mythology)">Roman god of war</a>. Mars is a <a href="/wiki/Terrestrial_planet" title="Terrestrial planet">terrestrial planet</a> with <a href="/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Mars" title="Atmosphere of Mars">a thin atmosphere</a> and has a crust primarily composed of elements similar to Earth's crust, as well as a core made of iron and nickel. Mars has surface features such as <a href="/wiki/Impact_crater" title="Impact crater">impact craters</a>, <a href="/wiki/Valley" title="Valley">valleys</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dune" title="Dune">dunes</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Polar_ice_caps" class="mw-redirect" title="Polar ice caps">polar ice caps</a>. Mars has two small, irregularly shaped moons, <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(moon)" title="Phobos (moon)">Phobos</a> and <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(moon)" title="Deimos (moon)">Deimos</a>.
</p><p>Some of the most notable surface features on Mars include <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Mons" title="Olympus Mons">Olympus Mons</a>, the largest <a href="/wiki/Volcano" title="Volcano">volcano</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_tallest_mountains_in_the_Solar_System" title="List of tallest mountains in the Solar System">highest-known mountain</a> in the Solar System, and <a href="/wiki/Valles_Marineris" title="Valles Marineris">Valles Marineris</a>, one of the largest <a href="/wiki/Canyon" title="Canyon">canyons</a> in the Solar System. The <a href="/wiki/North_Polar_Basin_(Mars)" title="North Polar Basin (Mars)">Borealis basin</a> in the Northern Hemisphere covers approximately 40% of the planet and may be a large impact feature.<sup id="cite_ref-northcraterguard_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-northcraterguard-22">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Timekeeping_on_Mars" title="Timekeeping on Mars">Days and seasons on Mars</a> are comparable to those of Earth, as the planets have a similar <a href="/wiki/Rotation_period" title="Rotation period">rotation period</a> and tilt of the <a href="/wiki/Rotation_around_a_fixed_axis" title="Rotation around a fixed axis">rotational axis</a> relative to the <a href="/wiki/Ecliptic" title="Ecliptic">ecliptic plane</a>. Liquid <a href="/wiki/Water_on_Mars" title="Water on Mars">water on the surface of Mars</a> cannot exist due to low atmospheric pressure, which is less than 1% of the atmospheric pressure on Earth.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa.gov_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa.gov-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> Both of Mars's polar ice caps appear to be made largely of water.<sup id="cite_ref-sci299_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sci299-25">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:3_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-26">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> In the distant past, Mars was likely wetter, and thus possibly more suited for life. It is not known whether <a href="/wiki/Life_on_Mars" title="Life on Mars">life has ever existed on Mars</a>.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Exploration_of_Mars" title="Exploration of Mars">Mars has been explored</a> by several <a href="/wiki/Uncrewed_spacecraft" title="Uncrewed spacecraft">uncrewed spacecraft</a>, beginning with <i><a href="/wiki/Mariner_4" title="Mariner 4">Mariner 4</a></i> in 1965. NASA's <i><a href="/wiki/Viking_program" title="Viking program">Viking 1</a></i> lander transmitted the first images from the Martian surface in 1976. Two countries have successfully deployed <a href="/wiki/Rover_(space_exploration)" title="Rover (space exploration)">rovers</a> on Mars, the United States first doing so with <i><a href="/wiki/Sojourner_(rover)" title="Sojourner (rover)">Sojourner</a></i> in 1997 and China with <i><a href="/wiki/Zhurong_(rover)" title="Zhurong (rover)">Zhurong</a></i> in 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-:4_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:4-27">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> There are also planned future missions to Mars, such as a <a href="/wiki/NASA-ESA_Mars_Sample_Return" title="NASA-ESA Mars Sample Return">NASA-ESA Mars Sample Return</a> set to happen in 2026, and the <a href="/wiki/Rosalind_Franklin_(rover)" title="Rosalind Franklin (rover)"><i>Rosalind Franklin</i> rover mission</a>, which was intended to launch in 2018 but was delayed to 2024 at the earliest, with a more likely launch date at 2028.
</p><p>Mars can be viewed from Earth with the naked eye, as can its <a href="/wiki/Mars_surface_color" title="Mars surface color">reddish coloring</a>. This appearance, due to the <a href="/wiki/Iron(III)_oxide" title="Iron(III) oxide">iron oxide</a> prevalent on its surface, has led to Mars often being called the <b>Red Planet</b>.<sup id="cite_ref-Rees2012_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rees2012-28">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_hematite_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa_hematite-29">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> It is among the <a href="/wiki/List_of_brightest_natural_objects_in_the_sky" title="List of brightest natural objects in the sky">brightest objects in Earth's sky</a>, with an <a href="/wiki/Apparent_magnitude" title="Apparent magnitude">apparent magnitude</a> that reaches −2.94, comparable to that of <a href="/wiki/Jupiter" title="Jupiter">Jupiter</a> and surpassed only by <a href="/wiki/Venus" title="Venus">Venus</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Moon" title="Moon">Moon</a> and the Sun.<sup id="cite_ref-Mallama_and_Hilton_17-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mallama_and_Hilton-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Mars has been observed since ancient times. Over the millennia it has been featured in culture and the arts in ways that have reflected humanity's growing knowledge of it.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Historical_observations">Historical observations</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_Mars_observation" title="History of Mars observation">History of Mars observation</a></div>
<p>The history of observations of Mars is marked by the oppositions of Mars when the planet is closest to Earth and hence is most easily visible, which occur every couple of years. Even more notable are the <a href="/wiki/Perihelic_opposition" class="mw-redirect" title="Perihelic opposition">perihelic oppositions</a> of Mars, which are distinguished because Mars is close to perihelion, making it even closer to Earth.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-30">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Ancient_and_medieval_observations">Ancient and medieval observations</span></h3>
<p>The ancient <a href="/wiki/Sumer" title="Sumer">Sumerians</a> named Mars <a href="/wiki/Nergal" title="Nergal">Nergal</a>, the god of war and plague. During Sumerian times, Nergal was a minor deity of little significance, but, during later times, his main cult center was the city of <a href="/wiki/Nineveh" title="Nineveh">Nineveh</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Rabkin2005_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rabkin2005-31">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> In Mesopotamian texts, Mars is referred to as the "star of judgement of the fate of the dead."<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> The existence of Mars as a wandering object in the night sky was also recorded by the ancient <a href="/wiki/Egyptian_astronomy" title="Egyptian astronomy">Egyptian astronomers</a> and, by 1534 BCE, they were familiar with the <a href="/wiki/Apparent_retrograde_motion" title="Apparent retrograde motion">retrograde motion</a> of the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-paob85_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-paob85-33">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> By the period of the <a href="/wiki/Neo-Babylonian_Empire" title="Neo-Babylonian Empire">Neo-Babylonian Empire</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Babylonian_astronomy" title="Babylonian astronomy">Babylonian astronomers</a> were making regular records of the positions of the planets and systematic observations of their behavior. For Mars, they knew that the planet made 37 <a href="/wiki/Orbital_period" title="Orbital period">synodic periods</a>, or 42 circuits of the zodiac, every 79 years. They invented arithmetic methods for making minor corrections to the predicted positions of the planets.<sup id="cite_ref-north08_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-north08-34">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-swerdlow98_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-swerdlow98-35">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">Ancient Greece</a>, the planet was known as <span title="Ancient Greek-language text"><span lang="grc"><a href="/wiki/Pyroeis" title="Pyroeis">Πυρόεις</a></span></span>.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> Commonly, the Greek name for the planet now referred to as Mars, was Ares. It was the Romans who named the planet Mars, for their god of war, often represented by the sword and shield of the planet's namesake.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the fourth century BCE, <a href="/wiki/Aristotle" title="Aristotle">Aristotle</a> noted that Mars disappeared behind the Moon during an <a href="/wiki/Occultation" title="Occultation">occultation</a>, indicating that the planet was farther away.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Ptolemy" title="Ptolemy">Ptolemy</a>, a Greek living in <a href="/wiki/Alexandria" title="Alexandria">Alexandria</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-harland_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-harland-39">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> attempted to address the problem of the orbital motion of Mars. Ptolemy's model and his collective work on astronomy was presented in the multi-volume collection later called the <i><a href="/wiki/Almagest" title="Almagest">Almagest</a></i> (from the Arabic for "greatest"), which became the authoritative treatise on <a href="/wiki/Medieval_astronomy" class="mw-redirect" title="Medieval astronomy">Western astronomy</a> for the next fourteen centuries.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> Literature from ancient China confirms that Mars was known by <a href="/wiki/Chinese_astronomy" title="Chinese astronomy">Chinese astronomers</a> by no later than the fourth century BCE.<sup id="cite_ref-needham_ronan85_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-needham_ronan85-41">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> In the <a href="/wiki/East_Asian" class="mw-redirect" title="East Asian">East Asian</a> cultures, Mars is traditionally referred to as the "fire star" (Chinese: <span title="Chinese-language text"><span lang="zh">火星</span></span>), based on the <a href="/wiki/Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)" title="Wuxing (Chinese philosophy)"><i>Wuxing</i> system</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>During the seventeenth century A.D., <a href="/wiki/Tycho_Brahe" title="Tycho Brahe">Tycho Brahe</a> measured the <a href="/wiki/Diurnal_parallax" class="mw-redirect" title="Diurnal parallax">diurnal parallax</a> of Mars that <a href="/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title="Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a> used to make a preliminary calculation of the relative distance to the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-taton03_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-taton03-45">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup> From Brahe's observations of Mars, Kepler deduced that the planet orbited the Sun not in a circle, but in an <a href="/wiki/Ellipse" title="Ellipse">ellipse</a>. Moreover, Kepler showed that Mars sped up as it approached the Sun and slowed down as it moved farther away, in a manner that later physicists would explain as a consequence of the <a href="/wiki/Conservation_of_angular_momentum" class="mw-redirect" title="Conservation of angular momentum">conservation of angular momentum</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-TMU_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TMU-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup><sup class="reference nowrap"><span title="Pages: 433–437">&#58;&#8202;433–437&#8202;</span></sup> When the telescope became available, the diurnal parallax of Mars was again measured in an effort to determine the Sun-Earth distance. This was first performed by <a href="/wiki/Giovanni_Domenico_Cassini" title="Giovanni Domenico Cassini">Giovanni Domenico Cassini</a> in 1672. The early parallax measurements were hampered by the quality of the instruments.<sup id="cite_ref-hirschfeld01_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hirschfeld01-47">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> The only <a href="/wiki/Occultation" title="Occultation">occultation</a> of Mars by Venus observed was that of 13 October 1590, seen by <a href="/wiki/Michael_Maestlin" title="Michael Maestlin">Michael Maestlin</a> at <a href="/wiki/Heidelberg" title="Heidelberg">Heidelberg</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-sat57_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sat57-48">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup> In 1610, Mars was viewed by Italian astronomer <a href="/wiki/Galileo_Galilei" title="Galileo Galilei">Galileo Galilei</a>, who was first to see it via telescope.<sup id="cite_ref-jha15_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jha15-49">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup> The first person to draw a map of Mars that displayed any terrain features was the Dutch astronomer <a href="/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens" title="Christiaan Huygens">Christiaan Huygens</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-arizona_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-arizona-50">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span id="Martian_.22canals.22"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Martian_&quot;canals&quot;">Martian "canals"</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Martian_canals" title="Martian canals">Martian canals</a></div>
<p>By the 19th century, the resolution of telescopes reached a level sufficient for surface features to be identified. On 5 September 1877, a perihelic opposition of Mars occurred. The Italian astronomer <a href="/wiki/Giovanni_Schiaparelli" title="Giovanni Schiaparelli">Giovanni Schiaparelli</a> used a 22-centimetre (8.7&#160;in) telescope in <a href="/wiki/Milan" title="Milan">Milan</a> to help produce the first detailed map of Mars. These maps notably contained features he called <i>canali</i>, which were later shown to be an <a href="/wiki/Optical_illusion" title="Optical illusion">optical illusion</a>. These <i>canali</i> were supposedly long, straight lines on the surface of Mars, to which he gave names of famous rivers on Earth. His term, which means "channels" or "grooves", was popularly mistranslated in English as "canals".<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sagan80_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sagan80-52">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Influenced by the observations, the orientalist <a href="/wiki/Percival_Lowell" title="Percival Lowell">Percival Lowell</a> founded <a href="/wiki/Lowell_Observatory" title="Lowell Observatory">an observatory</a> which had 30- and 45-centimetre (12- and 18-in) telescopes. The observatory was used for the exploration of Mars during the last good opportunity in 1894 and the following less favorable oppositions. He published several books on Mars and life on the planet, which had a great influence on the public.<sup id="cite_ref-basalla06_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-basalla06-53">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NYT-20151001_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-20151001-54">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> The <i>canali</i> were independently observed by other astronomers, like <a href="/wiki/Henri_Joseph_Perrotin" class="mw-redirect" title="Henri Joseph Perrotin">Henri Joseph Perrotin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Louis_Thollon" title="Louis Thollon">Louis Thollon</a> in Nice, using one of the largest telescopes of that time.<sup id="cite_ref-maria_lane05_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maria_lane05-55">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ba3_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ba3-56">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The seasonal changes (consisting of the diminishing of the polar caps and the dark areas formed during Martian summer) in combination with the canals led to speculation about life on Mars, and it was a long-held belief that Mars contained vast seas and vegetation. As bigger telescopes were used, fewer long, straight <i>canali</i> were observed. During observations in 1909 by <a href="/wiki/Antoniadi" class="mw-redirect" title="Antoniadi">Antoniadi</a> with an 84-centimetre (33&#160;in) telescope, irregular patterns were observed, but no <i>canali</i> were seen.<sup id="cite_ref-zahnle01_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zahnle01-57">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Physical_characteristics">Physical characteristics</span></h2>

<p>Mars is approximately half the diameter of Earth, with a surface area only slightly less than the total area of Earth's dry land.<sup id="cite_ref-NasaFactSheet_2-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NasaFactSheet-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Mars is less dense than Earth, having about 15% of Earth's volume and 11% of Earth's <a href="/wiki/Mass" title="Mass">mass</a>, resulting in about 38% of Earth's surface gravity. The red-orange appearance of the Martian surface is caused by <a href="/wiki/Iron(III)_oxide" title="Iron(III) oxide">ferric oxide</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Rust" title="Rust">rust</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-rust_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rust-58">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup> It can look like <a href="/wiki/Butterscotch" title="Butterscotch">butterscotch</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-ismars_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ismars-59">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> other common surface colors include golden, brown, tan, and greenish, depending on the <a href="/wiki/Mineral" title="Mineral">minerals</a> present.<sup id="cite_ref-ismars_59-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ismars-59">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Internal_structure">Internal structure</span></h3>
<p>Like Earth, Mars has <a href="/wiki/Planetary_differentiation" title="Planetary differentiation">differentiated</a> into a dense metallic <a href="/wiki/Planetary_core" title="Planetary core">core</a> overlaid by less dense materials.<sup id="cite_ref-Nimmo_2005_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Nimmo_2005-60">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-mars-in-depth_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mars-in-depth-61">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup> Current models of its interior imply a core consisting primarily of <a href="/wiki/Iron%E2%80%93nickel_alloy" title="Iron–nickel alloy">iron and nickel</a> with about 16–17% <a href="/wiki/Sulfur" title="Sulfur">sulfur</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-icarus213_2_451_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-icarus213_2_451-62">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup> This <a href="/wiki/Iron(II)_sulfide" title="Iron(II) sulfide">iron(II) sulfide</a> core is thought to be twice as rich in lighter elements as Earth's.<sup id="cite_ref-jacque03_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jacque03-63">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> The core is surrounded by a silicate <a href="/wiki/Mantle_(geology)" title="Mantle (geology)">mantle</a> that formed many of the <a href="/wiki/Tectonics_of_Mars" title="Tectonics of Mars">tectonic</a> and volcanic features on the planet, but it appears to be dormant. Besides silicon and oxygen, the most abundant elements in the Martian <a href="/wiki/Crust_(geology)" title="Crust (geology)">crust</a> are <a href="/wiki/Iron" title="Iron">iron</a>, <a href="/wiki/Magnesium" title="Magnesium">magnesium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aluminium" title="Aluminium">aluminium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Calcium" title="Calcium">calcium</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Potassium" title="Potassium">potassium</a>. The average thickness of the planet's crust is about 50 kilometres (31&#160;mi), with a maximum thickness of 125 kilometres (78&#160;mi).<sup id="cite_ref-jacque03_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jacque03-63">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> By comparison, Earth's crust averages 40 kilometres (25&#160;mi) in thickness.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Knapmeyer-Endrun2021_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Knapmeyer-Endrun2021-65">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars is seismically active. In 2019, it was reported that <a href="/wiki/InSight" title="InSight">InSight</a> (now offline) had detected and recorded over 450 <a href="/wiki/Marsquake" title="Marsquake">marsquakes</a> and related events.<sup id="cite_ref-natco_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-natco-66">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-natgeo_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-natgeo-67">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup> In 2021 it was reported that based on eleven low-frequency marsquakes detected by the <i>InSight</i> lander the core of Mars was indeed liquid and had a radius of about <span class="nowrap"><span data-sort-value="7006183000000000000♠"></span>1830<span style="margin-left:0.3em;margin-right:0.15em;">±</span>40&#160;km</span> and a temperature around 1900–2000&#160;K. The Martian core radius is abnormally large, accounting for more than half the radius of Mars and about half the size of the Earth's core. To this, it has been suggested that the core contains some amount of lighter <a href="/wiki/Chemical_element" title="Chemical element">elements</a> like <a href="/wiki/Oxygen" title="Oxygen">oxygen</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen" title="Hydrogen">hydrogen</a> in addition to the iron–nickel alloy and about 15% of sulfur.<sup id="cite_ref-PHYS-20210319_68-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-PHYS-20210319-68">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Stähler_69-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stähler-69">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The core of Mars is overlaid by the rocky mantle, which does not seem to have a thermally insulating layer analogous to the Earth's <a href="/wiki/Lower_mantle" class="mw-redirect" title="Lower mantle">lower mantle</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Stähler_69-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stähler-69">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup> The Martian mantle appears to be solid down to the depth of about 500&#160;km, where the <a href="/wiki/Low-velocity_zone" title="Low-velocity zone">low-velocity zone</a> (partially melted <a href="/wiki/Asthenosphere" title="Asthenosphere">asthenosphere</a>) begins.<sup id="cite_ref-Khan2021_70-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Khan2021-70">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup> Below the asthenosphere the velocity of seismic waves starts to grow again; and at the depth of about 1050&#160;km lies the boundary of the <a href="/wiki/Transition_zone_(Earth)" title="Transition zone (Earth)">transition zone</a> extending down to the core.<sup id="cite_ref-Stähler_69-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stähler-69">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Surface_geology">Surface geology</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Geology_of_Mars" title="Geology of Mars">Geology of Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png/300px-USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="338" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png/450px-USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1f/USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png/600px-USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png 2x" data-file-width="3773" data-file-height="4249" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:USGS-MarsMap-sim3292-20140714-crop.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Geology_of_Mars" title="Geology of Mars">Geologic map</a> of Mars (<a href="/wiki/USGS" class="mw-redirect" title="USGS">USGS</a>, 2014)<sup id="cite_ref-USGS-20140714_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USGS-20140714-71">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>
<p>Mars is a <a href="/wiki/Terrestrial_planet" title="Terrestrial planet">terrestrial planet</a> with a surface that consists of minerals containing <a href="/wiki/Silicon" title="Silicon">silicon</a> and oxygen, <a href="/wiki/Metal" title="Metal">metals</a>, and other elements that typically make up <a href="/wiki/Rock_(geology)" title="Rock (geology)">rock</a>. The Martian surface is primarily composed of <a href="/wiki/Tholeiitic_magma_series" title="Tholeiitic magma series">tholeiitic</a> <a href="/wiki/Basalt" title="Basalt">basalt</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-science324_5928_736_72-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-science324_5928_736-72">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> although parts are more <a href="/wiki/Silica" class="mw-redirect" title="Silica">silica</a>-rich than typical basalt and may be similar to <a href="/wiki/Andesitic" class="mw-redirect" title="Andesitic">andesitic</a> rocks on Earth, or silica glass. Regions of low <a href="/wiki/Albedo" title="Albedo">albedo</a> suggest concentrations of <a href="/wiki/Plagioclase_feldspar" class="mw-redirect" title="Plagioclase feldspar">plagioclase feldspar</a>, with northern low albedo regions displaying higher than normal concentrations of sheet silicates and high-silicon glass. Parts of the southern highlands include detectable amounts of high-calcium <a href="/wiki/Pyroxenes" class="mw-redirect" title="Pyroxenes">pyroxenes</a>. Localized concentrations of <a href="/wiki/Hematite" title="Hematite">hematite</a> and <a href="/wiki/Olivine" title="Olivine">olivine</a> have been found.<sup id="cite_ref-jgr107_E6_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jgr107_E6-73">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup> Much of the surface is deeply covered by finely grained <a href="/wiki/Iron(III)_oxide" title="Iron(III) oxide">iron(III) oxide</a> dust.<sup id="cite_ref-sci300a_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sci300a-74">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Although Mars has no evidence of a structured <a href="/wiki/Magnetic_field_of_Mars" title="Magnetic field of Mars">global magnetic field</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-magnetosphere_75-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-magnetosphere-75">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> observations show that parts of the planet's crust have been magnetized, suggesting that alternating polarity reversals of its dipole field have occurred in the past. This <a href="/wiki/Paleomagnetism" title="Paleomagnetism">paleomagnetism</a> of magnetically susceptible minerals is similar to the <a href="/wiki/Plate_tectonics" title="Plate tectonics">alternating bands found on Earth's ocean floors</a>. One theory, published in 1999 and re-examined in October&#160;2005 (with the help of the <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Global_Surveyor" title="Mars Global Surveyor">Mars Global Surveyor</a></i>), is that these bands suggest <a href="/wiki/Plate_tectonics" title="Plate tectonics">plate tectonic activity</a> on Mars four billion years ago, before the planetary <a href="/wiki/Dynamo_theory" title="Dynamo theory">dynamo</a> ceased to function and the planet's magnetic field faded.<sup id="cite_ref-plates_76-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plates-76">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Scientists have theorized that during the <a href="/wiki/Formation_and_evolution_of_the_Solar_System" title="Formation and evolution of the Solar System">Solar System's formation</a> Mars was created as the result of a <a href="/wiki/Stochastic_process" title="Stochastic process">random process</a> of run-away accretion of material from the <a href="/wiki/Protoplanetary_disk" title="Protoplanetary disk">protoplanetary disk</a> that orbited the Sun. Mars has many distinctive chemical features caused by its position in the Solar System. Elements with comparatively low boiling points, such as <a href="/wiki/Chlorine" title="Chlorine">chlorine</a>, <a href="/wiki/Phosphorus" title="Phosphorus">phosphorus</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Sulfur" title="Sulfur">sulfur</a>, are much more common on Mars than Earth; these elements were probably pushed outward by the young Sun's energetic <a href="/wiki/Solar_wind" title="Solar wind">solar wind</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ssr96_1_4_197_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ssr96_1_4_197-77">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>After the formation of the planets, all were subjected to the so-called "<a href="/wiki/Late_Heavy_Bombardment" title="Late Heavy Bombardment">Late Heavy Bombardment</a>". About 60% of the surface of Mars shows a record of impacts from that era,<sup id="cite_ref-zharkov93_78-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zharkov93-78">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-icarus165_1_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-icarus165_1-79">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-barlow88_80-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-barlow88-80">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup> whereas much of the remaining surface is probably underlain by immense impact basins caused by those events. There is evidence of an enormous impact basin in the Northern Hemisphere of Mars, spanning 10,600 by 8,500 kilometres (6,600 by 5,300&#160;mi), or roughly four times the size of the Moon's <a href="/wiki/South_Pole_%E2%80%93_Aitken_basin" class="mw-redirect" title="South Pole – Aitken basin">South Pole – Aitken basin</a>, the largest impact basin yet discovered.<sup id="cite_ref-northcratersn_81-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-northcratersn-81">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup> This theory suggests that Mars was struck by a <a href="/wiki/Pluto" title="Pluto">Pluto</a>-sized body about four billion years ago. The event, thought to be the cause of the <a href="/wiki/Martian_hemispheric_dichotomy" class="mw-redirect" title="Martian hemispheric dichotomy">Martian hemispheric dichotomy</a>, created the smooth <a href="/wiki/Borealis_basin" class="mw-redirect" title="Borealis basin">Borealis basin</a> that covers 40% of the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-sciam080627_82-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sciam080627-82">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nyt080626_83-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt080626-83">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The geological history of Mars can be split into many periods, but the following are the three primary periods:<sup id="cite_ref-jog91_84-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jog91-84">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ssr_96_1_4_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ssr_96_1_4-85">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Noachian" title="Noachian">Noachian</a> period: Formation of the oldest extant surfaces of Mars, 4.5 to 3.5&#160;billion years ago. Noachian age surfaces are scarred by many large impact craters. The <a href="/wiki/Tharsis" title="Tharsis">Tharsis</a> bulge, a volcanic upland, is thought to have formed during this period, with extensive flooding by liquid water late in the period. Named after <a href="/wiki/Noachis_Terra" title="Noachis Terra">Noachis Terra</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-86">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hesperian" title="Hesperian">Hesperian</a> period: 3.5 to between 3.3 and 2.9&#160;billion years ago. The Hesperian period is marked by the formation of extensive lava plains. Named after <a href="/wiki/Hesperia_Planum" title="Hesperia Planum">Hesperia Planum</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_86-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-86">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amazonian_(Mars)" title="Amazonian (Mars)">Amazonian</a> period: between 3.3 and 2.9&#160;billion years ago to the present. Amazonian regions have few <a href="/wiki/Impact_event" title="Impact event">meteorite impact</a> craters but are otherwise quite varied. <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Mons" title="Olympus Mons">Olympus Mons</a> formed during this period, with lava flows elsewhere on Mars. Named after <a href="/wiki/Amazonis_Planitia" title="Amazonis Planitia">Amazonis Planitia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_86-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-86">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Geological activity is still taking place on Mars. The <a href="/wiki/Athabasca_Valles" title="Athabasca Valles">Athabasca Valles</a> is home to sheet-like lava flows created about 200&#160;<a href="/wiki/Myr" title="Myr">mya</a>. Water flows in the <a href="/wiki/Graben" title="Graben">grabens</a> called the <a href="/wiki/Cerberus_Fossae" title="Cerberus Fossae">Cerberus Fossae</a> occurred less than 20&#160;Mya, indicating equally recent volcanic intrusions.<sup id="cite_ref-ag44_4_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ag44_4-87">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> The <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter" title="Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i> has captured images of avalanches.<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Soil">Soil</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Martian_soil" title="Martian soil">Martian soil</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg/220px-PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="145" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg/330px-PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg/440px-PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4326" data-file-height="2856" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA17944-MarsCuriosityRover-AfterCrossingDingoGapSanddune-20140209.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)" title="Curiosity (rover)">Curiosity</a></i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">&#39;s</span> view of Martian soil and boulders after crossing the "Dingo Gap" <a href="/wiki/Sand_dune" class="mw-redirect" title="Sand dune">sand dune</a></div></div></div>
<p>The <i><a href="/wiki/Phoenix_(spacecraft)" title="Phoenix (spacecraft)">Phoenix</a></i> lander returned data showing Martian soil to be slightly alkaline and containing elements such as <a href="/wiki/Magnesium" title="Magnesium">magnesium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sodium" title="Sodium">sodium</a>, <a href="/wiki/Potassium" title="Potassium">potassium</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chlorine" title="Chlorine">chlorine</a>. These nutrients are found in soils on Earth. They are necessary for growth of plants.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc080627_90-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc080627-90">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup> Experiments performed by the lander showed that the Martian soil has a <a href="/wiki/Base_(chemistry)" title="Base (chemistry)">basic</a> <a href="/wiki/PH" title="PH">pH</a> of 7.7, and contains 0.6% of the <a href="/wiki/Salt_(chemistry)" title="Salt (chemistry)">salt</a> <a href="/wiki/Perchlorate" title="Perchlorate">perchlorate</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup> concentrations that are <a href="/wiki/Martian_soil#Toxicity" title="Martian soil">toxic to humans</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-toxicmars_93-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-toxicmars-93">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-toxicsoil1_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-toxicsoil1-94">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Dark_slope_streak" title="Dark slope streak">Streaks</a> are common across Mars and new ones appear frequently on steep slopes of craters, troughs, and valleys. The streaks are dark at first and get lighter with age. The streaks can start in a tiny area, then spread out for hundreds of metres. They have been seen to follow the edges of boulders and other obstacles in their path. The commonly accepted theories include that they are dark underlying layers of soil revealed after avalanches of bright dust or <a href="/wiki/Dust_devil" title="Dust devil">dust devils</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-jpl_dust_devil_95-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jpl_dust_devil-95">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup> Several other explanations have been put forward, including those that involve water or even the growth of organisms.<sup id="cite_ref-gpl29_23_41_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gpl29_23_41-96">&#91;95&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-oleb33_4_515_97-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-oleb33_4_515-97">&#91;96&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Hydrology">Hydrology</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Water_on_Mars" title="Water on Mars">Water on Mars</a></div><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1096954695/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"/><div class="thumb tmulti tleft"><div class="thumbinner multiimageinner" style="width:304px;max-width:304px"><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:302px;max-width:302px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_Viking_21i093.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Mars_Viking_21i093.png/300px-Mars_Viking_21i093.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="301" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Mars_Viking_21i093.png/450px-Mars_Viking_21i093.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7a/Mars_Viking_21i093.png 2x" data-file-width="510" data-file-height="512" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">Martian plain covered by water ice, precipitated through adhering to <a href="/wiki/Dry_ice" title="Dry ice">dry ice</a>, observed by <a href="/wiki/Viking_2" title="Viking 2">Viking 2</a> lander</div></div></div><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:302px;max-width:302px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="/wiki/File:Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg/300px-Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg" decoding="async" width="300" height="200" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg/450px-Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg/600px-Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_lower_latitudes_of_Mars_01.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3187" data-file-height="2125" /></a></div></div></div><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:302px;max-width:302px"><div class="thumbimage"><a href="/wiki/File:Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg/300px-Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg" decoding="async" width="300" height="200" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg/450px-Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg/600px-Water_equivalent_hydrogen_abundance_in_the_high_latitudes_of_Mars.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3187" data-file-height="2125" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">Proportion of water ice present in the upper meter of the Martian surface for lower (top) and higher (bottom) latitudes</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Water in its liquid form cannot exist on the surface of Mars due to low atmospheric pressure, which is less than 1% that of Earth's,<sup id="cite_ref-nasa.gov_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa.gov-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> except at the lowest of elevations for short periods.<sup id="cite_ref-mars-in-depth_61-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mars-in-depth-61">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-jgr110_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jgr110-98">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup> The two polar ice caps appear to be made largely of water.<sup id="cite_ref-sci299_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sci299-25">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:3_26-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-26">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> The volume of water ice in the south polar ice cap, if melted, would be enough to cover the entire surface of the planet with a depth of 11 metres (36&#160;ft).<sup id="cite_ref-nasa070315_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa070315-99">&#91;98&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Water_on_terrestrial_planets_of_the_Solar_System" title="Water on terrestrial planets of the Solar System">Large quantities of ice</a> are thought to be trapped within the thick <a href="/wiki/Cryosphere" title="Cryosphere">cryosphere</a> of Mars. Radar data from <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Express" title="Mars Express">Mars Express</a></i> and the <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter" title="Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i> (MRO) show large quantities of ice at both poles,<sup id="cite_ref-specials1_100-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-specials1-100">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-bbc040124_101-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc040124-101">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup> and at middle latitudes.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">&#91;101&#93;</a></sup> The Phoenix lander directly sampled water ice in shallow Martian soil on 31 July 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-spacecraft1_103-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spacecraft1-103">&#91;102&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Geomorphology" title="Geomorphology">Landforms</a> visible on Mars strongly suggest that liquid water has existed on the planet's surface. Huge linear swathes of scoured ground, known as <a href="/wiki/Outflow_channels" title="Outflow channels">outflow channels</a>, cut across the surface in about 25 places. These are thought to be a record of erosion caused by the catastrophic release of water from subsurface aquifers, though some of these structures have been hypothesized to result from the action of glaciers or lava.<sup id="cite_ref-Kerr2005_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kerr2005-104">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Jaeger2007_105-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Jaeger2007-105">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup> One of the larger examples, <a href="/wiki/Ma%27adim_Vallis" class="mw-redirect" title="Ma&#39;adim Vallis">Ma'adim Vallis</a>, is 700 kilometres (430&#160;mi) long, much greater than the Grand Canyon, with a width of 20 kilometres (12&#160;mi) and a depth of 2 kilometres (1.2&#160;mi) in places. It is thought to have been carved by flowing water early in Mars's history.<sup id="cite_ref-lucchita_rosanova_106-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lucchita_rosanova-106">&#91;105&#93;</a></sup> The youngest of these channels are thought to have formed only a few million years ago.<sup id="cite_ref-nature434_107-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nature434-107">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup> Elsewhere, particularly on the oldest areas of the Martian surface, finer-scale, dendritic <a href="/wiki/Valley_networks_(Mars)" class="mw-redirect" title="Valley networks (Mars)">networks of valleys</a> are spread across significant proportions of the landscape. Features of these valleys and their distribution strongly imply that they were carved by <a href="/wiki/Surface_runoff" title="Surface runoff">runoff</a> resulting from precipitation in early Mars history. Subsurface water flow and <a href="/wiki/Groundwater_sapping" title="Groundwater sapping">groundwater sapping</a> may play important subsidiary roles in some networks, but precipitation was probably the root cause of the incision in almost all cases.<sup id="cite_ref-CraddockHoward2002_108-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CraddockHoward2002-108">&#91;107&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Along crater and canyon walls, there are thousands of features that appear similar to terrestrial <a href="/wiki/Gullies" class="mw-redirect" title="Gullies">gullies</a>. The gullies tend to be in the highlands of the Southern Hemisphere and to face the Equator; all are poleward of 30° latitude. A number of authors have suggested that their formation process involves liquid water, probably from melting ice,<sup id="cite_ref-sci288_109-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sci288-109">&#91;108&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nasa061206_110-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa061206-110">&#91;109&#93;</a></sup> although others have argued for formation mechanisms involving carbon dioxide frost or the movement of dry dust.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc061206_111-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc061206-111">&#91;110&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nasa061206b_112-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa061206b-112">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup> No partially degraded gullies have formed by weathering and no superimposed impact craters have been observed, indicating that these are young features, possibly still active.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa061206_110-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa061206-110">&#91;109&#93;</a></sup> Other geological features, such as <a href="/wiki/River_delta" title="River delta">deltas</a> and <a href="/wiki/Alluvial_fans" class="mw-redirect" title="Alluvial fans">alluvial fans</a> preserved in craters, are further evidence for warmer, wetter conditions at an interval or intervals in earlier Mars history.<sup id="cite_ref-Lewis2006_113-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lewis2006-113">&#91;112&#93;</a></sup> Such conditions necessarily require the widespread presence of <a href="/wiki/Volcanic_crater_lake" title="Volcanic crater lake">crater lakes</a> across a large proportion of the surface, for which there is independent mineralogical, sedimentological and geomorphological evidence.<sup id="cite_ref-Matsubara2011_114-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Matsubara2011-114">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup> Further evidence that liquid water once existed on the surface of Mars comes from the detection of specific minerals such as <a href="/wiki/Hematite" title="Hematite">hematite</a> and <a href="/wiki/Goethite" title="Goethite">goethite</a>, both of which sometimes form in the presence of water.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa040303_115-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa040303-115">&#91;114&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Polar_caps">Polar caps</span></h4>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Martian_polar_ice_caps" title="Martian polar ice caps">Martian polar ice caps</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1096954695/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"/><div class="thumb tmulti tright"><div class="thumbinner multiimageinner" style="width:392px;max-width:392px"><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:167px;max-width:167px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:159px;overflow:hidden"><a href="/wiki/File:Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg/165px-Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg" decoding="async" width="165" height="159" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg/248px-Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg/330px-Martian_north_polar_cap.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1368" data-file-height="1319" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">North polar early summer water ice cap (1999); a seasonal layer of carbon dioxide ice forms in winter and disappears in summer.</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:221px;max-width:221px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:159px;overflow:hidden"><a href="/wiki/File:South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg/219px-South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg" decoding="async" width="219" height="160" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg/329px-South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg/438px-South_Polar_Cap_of_Mars_during_Martian_South_summer_2000.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1690" data-file-height="1234" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">South polar midsummer ice cap (2000); the south cap has a permanent carbon dioxide ice cap covered with water ice.<sup id="cite_ref-Barlow_2008_116-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Barlow_2008-116">&#91;115&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Mars has two permanent polar ice caps. During a pole's winter, it lies in continuous darkness, chilling the surface and causing the <a href="/wiki/Deposition_(phase_transition)" title="Deposition (phase transition)">deposition</a> of 25–30% of the atmosphere into slabs of <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">CO<sub>2</sub></a> ice (<a href="/wiki/Dry_ice" title="Dry ice">dry ice</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-icarus169_117-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-icarus169-117">&#91;116&#93;</a></sup> When the poles are again exposed to sunlight, the frozen CO<sub>2</sub> <a href="/wiki/Sublimation_(physics)" class="mw-redirect" title="Sublimation (physics)">sublimes</a>. These seasonal actions transport large amounts of dust and water vapor, giving rise to Earth-like frost and large <a href="/wiki/Cirrus_cloud" title="Cirrus cloud">cirrus clouds</a>. Clouds of water-ice were photographed by the <i><a href="/wiki/Opportunity_(rover)" title="Opportunity (rover)">Opportunity</a></i> rover in 2004.<sup id="cite_ref-clouds_118-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-clouds-118">&#91;117&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The caps at both poles consist primarily (70%) of water ice. Frozen carbon dioxide accumulates as a comparatively thin layer about one metre thick on the north cap in the northern winter only, whereas the south cap has a permanent dry ice cover about eight metres thick. This permanent dry ice cover at the south pole is peppered by <a href="/wiki/Swiss_cheese_features" title="Swiss cheese features">flat floored, shallow, roughly circular pits</a>, which repeat imaging shows are expanding in some places and retreating in others.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">&#91;118&#93;</a></sup> The northern polar cap has a diameter of about 1,000 kilometres (620&#160;mi),<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120">&#91;119&#93;</a></sup> and contains about 1.6&#160;million cubic kilometres (5.7<span style="margin:0 .15em 0 .25em">×</span>10<sup>16</sup>&#160;cu&#160;ft) of ice, which, if spread evenly on the cap, would be 2 kilometres (1.2&#160;mi) thick.<sup id="cite_ref-brown_121-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-brown-121">&#91;120&#93;</a></sup> (This compares to a volume of 2.85&#160;million cubic kilometres (1.01<span style="margin:0 .15em 0 .25em">×</span>10<sup>17</sup>&#160;cu&#160;ft) for the <a href="/wiki/Greenland_ice_sheet" title="Greenland ice sheet">Greenland ice sheet</a>.) The southern polar cap has a diameter of 350 kilometres (220&#160;mi) and a thickness of 3 kilometres (1.9&#160;mi).<sup id="cite_ref-phillips_122-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-phillips-122">&#91;121&#93;</a></sup> The total volume of ice in the south polar cap plus the adjacent layered deposits has been estimated at 1.6&#160;million cubic km.<sup id="cite_ref-sci315_123-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sci315-123">&#91;122&#93;</a></sup> Both polar caps show spiral troughs, which recent analysis of <a href="/wiki/SHARAD" title="SHARAD">SHARAD</a> ice penetrating radar has shown are a result of <a href="/wiki/Katabatic_wind" title="Katabatic wind">katabatic winds</a> that spiral due to the <a href="/wiki/Coriolis_force" title="Coriolis force">Coriolis effect</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Onset_and_migration_of_spiral_troughs_on_Mars_revealed_by_orbital_radar_124-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Onset_and_migration_of_spiral_troughs_on_Mars_revealed_by_orbital_radar-124">&#91;123&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Mystery_Spirals_on_Mars_Finally_Explained_125-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mystery_Spirals_on_Mars_Finally_Explained-125">&#91;124&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The seasonal frosting of areas near the southern ice cap results in the formation of transparent 1-metre-thick slabs of dry ice above the ground. With the arrival of spring, sunlight warms the subsurface and pressure from subliming CO<sub>2</sub> builds up under a slab, elevating and ultimately rupturing it. This leads to <a href="/wiki/Martian_geyser" class="mw-redirect" title="Martian geyser">geyser-like eruptions</a> of CO<sub>2</sub> gas mixed with dark basaltic sand or dust. This process is rapid, observed happening in the space of a few days, weeks or months, a rate of change rather unusual in geology – especially for Mars. The gas rushing underneath a slab to the site of a geyser carves a spiderweb-like pattern of radial channels under the ice, the process being the inverted equivalent of an erosion network formed by water draining through a single plughole.<sup id="cite_ref-126" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-126">&#91;125&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Observations_and_findings_of_water_evidence">Observations and findings of water evidence</span></h4>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Chronology_of_discoveries_of_water_on_Mars" title="Chronology of discoveries of water on Mars">Chronology of discoveries of water on Mars</a></div>
<p>In 2004, <i>Opportunity</i> detected the mineral <a href="/wiki/Jarosite" title="Jarosite">jarosite</a>. This forms only in the presence of acidic water, showing that water once existed on Mars.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa101001_128-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa101001-128">&#91;127&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-129">&#91;128&#93;</a></sup> The <i>Spirit</i> rover found concentrated deposits of <a href="/wiki/Silica" class="mw-redirect" title="Silica">silica</a> in 2007 that indicated wet conditions in the past, and in December 2011, the mineral <a href="/wiki/Gypsum" title="Gypsum">gypsum</a>, which also forms in the presence of water, was found on the surface by NASA's Mars rover Opportunity.<sup id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-130">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_131-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa-131">&#91;130&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nationalgeographic_132-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nationalgeographic-132">&#91;131&#93;</a></sup> It is estimated that the amount of water in the upper mantle of Mars, represented by <a href="/wiki/Hydroxyl_ion" class="mw-redirect" title="Hydroxyl ion">hydroxyl ions</a> contained within Martian minerals, is equal to or greater than that of Earth at 50–300 parts per million of water, which is enough to cover the entire planet to a depth of 200–1,000 metres (660–3,280&#160;ft).<sup id="cite_ref-nationalgeographic1_133-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nationalgeographic1-133">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134">&#91;133&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg/220px-Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="158" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg/330px-Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg/440px-Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg 2x" data-file-width="945" data-file-height="680" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_exposed_subsurface_ice.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>A cross-section of underground water ice is exposed at the steep slope that appears bright blue in this enhanced-color view from the <a href="/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter" title="Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter">MRO</a>.</div></div></div>
<p>On 18 March 2013, <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a> reported evidence from instruments on the <a href="/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)" title="Curiosity (rover)"><i>Curiosity</i> rover</a> of <a href="/wiki/Mineral_hydration" title="Mineral hydration">mineral hydration</a>, likely hydrated <a href="/wiki/Calcium_sulfate" title="Calcium sulfate">calcium sulfate</a>, in several <a href="/wiki/Rock_(geology)" title="Rock (geology)">rock samples</a> including the broken fragments of <a href="/wiki/Tintina_(rock)" title="Tintina (rock)">"Tintina" rock</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_rocks_on_Mars#Curiosity" title="List of rocks on Mars">"Sutton Inlier" rock</a> as well as in <a href="/wiki/Vein_(geology)" title="Vein (geology)">veins</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nodule_(geology)" title="Nodule (geology)">nodules</a> in other rocks like <a href="/wiki/List_of_rocks_on_Mars#Curiosity" title="List of rocks on Mars">"Knorr" rock</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_rocks_on_Mars#Curiosity" title="List of rocks on Mars">"Wernicke" rock</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NASA-20130318_135-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA-20130318-135">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-BBC-20130319_136-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BBC-20130319-136">&#91;135&#93;</a></sup> Analysis using the rover's <a href="/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)#Dynamic_Albedo_of_Neutrons_(DAN)" title="Curiosity (rover)">DAN instrument</a> provided evidence of subsurface water, amounting to as much as 4% water content, down to a depth of 60 centimetres (24&#160;in), during the rover's traverse from the <i><a href="/wiki/Bradbury_Landing" title="Bradbury Landing">Bradbury Landing</a></i> site to the <i>Yellowknife Bay</i> area in the <i><a href="/wiki/Glenelg,_Mars" title="Glenelg, Mars">Glenelg</a></i> terrain.<sup id="cite_ref-NASA-20130318_135-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA-20130318-135">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup> In September 2015, NASA announced that they had found strong evidence of hydrated <a href="/wiki/Brine" title="Brine">brine</a> flows in <a href="/wiki/Recurring_slope_lineae" class="mw-redirect" title="Recurring slope lineae">recurring slope lineae</a>, based on spectrometer readings of the darkened areas of slopes.<sup id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137">&#91;136&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138">&#91;137&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Ojhaetal2015_139-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ojhaetal2015-139">&#91;138&#93;</a></sup> These streaks flow downhill in Martian summer, when the temperature is above −23° Celsius, and freeze at lower temperatures.<sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup> These observations supported earlier hypotheses, based on timing of formation and their rate of growth, that these dark streaks resulted from water flowing just below the surface.<sup id="cite_ref-SeasonalFlows_141-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SeasonalFlows-141">&#91;140&#93;</a></sup> However, later work suggested that the lineae may be dry, granular flows instead, with at most a limited role for water in initiating the process.<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142">&#91;141&#93;</a></sup> A definitive conclusion about the presence, extent, and role of liquid water on the Martian surface remains elusive.<sup id="cite_ref-143" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143">&#91;142&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">&#91;143&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Researchers suspect much of the low northern plains of the planet were <a href="/wiki/Mars_ocean_hypothesis" title="Mars ocean hypothesis">covered with an ocean</a> hundreds of meters deep, though this theory remains controversial.<sup id="cite_ref-Head1999_145-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Head1999-145">&#91;144&#93;</a></sup> In March 2015, scientists stated that such an ocean might have been the size of Earth's <a href="/wiki/Arctic_Ocean" title="Arctic Ocean">Arctic Ocean</a>. This finding was derived from the ratio of <a href="/wiki/Protium_(isotope)" class="mw-redirect" title="Protium (isotope)">protium</a> to <a href="/wiki/Deuterium" title="Deuterium">deuterium</a> in the modern Martian atmosphere compared to that ratio on Earth. The amount of Martian deuterium is eight times the amount that exists on Earth, suggesting that ancient Mars had significantly higher levels of water. Results from the <i>Curiosity</i> rover had previously found a high ratio of deuterium in <a href="/wiki/Gale_Crater" class="mw-redirect" title="Gale Crater">Gale Crater</a>, though not significantly high enough to suggest the former presence of an ocean. Other scientists caution that these results have not been confirmed, and point out that Martian climate models have not yet shown that the planet was warm enough in the past to support bodies of liquid water.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT-20150305_146-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-20150305-146">&#91;145&#93;</a></sup> Near the northern polar cap is the 81.4 kilometres (50.6&#160;mi) wide <a href="/wiki/Korolev_(Martian_crater)" title="Korolev (Martian crater)">Korolev Crater</a>, which the <a href="/wiki/Mars_Express" title="Mars Express">Mars Express</a> orbiter found to be filled with approximately 2,200 cubic kilometres (530&#160;cu&#160;mi) of water ice.<sup id="cite_ref-TG1218_147-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TG1218-147">&#91;146&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In November 2016, NASA reported finding a large amount of underground ice in the <a href="/wiki/Utopia_Planitia" title="Utopia Planitia">Utopia Planitia</a> region. The volume of water detected has been estimated to be equivalent to the volume of water in <a href="/wiki/Lake_Superior" title="Lake Superior">Lake Superior</a> (which is 12,100 cubic kilometres<sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">&#91;147&#93;</a></sup>).<sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">&#91;148&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NASA-20161122_150-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA-20161122-150">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup> During observations from 2018 through 2021, the ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter spotted indications of water, probably subsurface ice, in the Valles Marineris canyon system.<sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">&#91;150&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Geography_and_names">Geography and names</span></h3>
<p><span class="anchor" id="Geography"></span>
</p>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Geography_of_Mars" class="mw-redirect" title="Geography of Mars">Geography of Mars</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Areoid" class="mw-redirect" title="Areoid">Areoid</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Category:Surface_features_of_Mars" title="Category:Surface features of Mars">Category:Surface features of Mars</a></div>
<div class="center"><div class="thumb tnone"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:602px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_topography_(MOLA_dataset)_with_poles_HiRes.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Mars_topography_%28MOLA_dataset%29_with_poles_HiRes.jpg/600px-Mars_topography_%28MOLA_dataset%29_with_poles_HiRes.jpg" decoding="async" width="600" height="270" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Mars_topography_%28MOLA_dataset%29_with_poles_HiRes.jpg/900px-Mars_topography_%28MOLA_dataset%29_with_poles_HiRes.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Mars_topography_%28MOLA_dataset%29_with_poles_HiRes.jpg/1200px-Mars_topography_%28MOLA_dataset%29_with_poles_HiRes.jpg 2x" data-file-width="15400" data-file-height="6940" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_topography_(MOLA_dataset)_with_poles_HiRes.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>A <a href="/wiki/Mars_Orbiter_Laser_Altimeter" title="Mars Orbiter Laser Altimeter">MOLA</a>-based topographic map showing highlands (red and orange) dominating the Southern Hemisphere of Mars, lowlands (blue) the northern. Volcanic plateaus delimit regions of the northern plains, whereas the highlands are punctuated by several large impact basins.</div></div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width: 272px;">
<div class="thumbimage" style="width: 270px; height: 300px; overflow: hidden;">
<div style="position: relative; top: -1520px; left: -1890px; width: 4050px"><div class="noresize"><a href="/wiki/File:Map_of_Mars.png" class="image"><img alt="Terminology of Martian geological features" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Map_of_Mars.png/4050px-Map_of_Mars.png" decoding="async" width="4050" height="2113" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/75/Map_of_Mars.png 1.5x" data-file-width="4600" data-file-height="2400" /></a></div></div>
</div>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Map_of_Mars.png" title="File:Map of Mars.png"> </a></div>Terminology of Martian geological features
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Although better remembered for mapping the Moon, <a href="/wiki/Johann_Heinrich_M%C3%A4dler" class="mw-redirect" title="Johann Heinrich Mädler">Johann Heinrich Mädler</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wilhelm_Beer" title="Wilhelm Beer">Wilhelm Beer</a> were the first areographers. They began by establishing that most of Mars's surface features were permanent and by more precisely determining the planet's rotation period. In 1840, Mädler combined ten years of observations and drew the first map of Mars.<sup id="cite_ref-152" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-152">&#91;151&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Features on Mars are named from a variety of sources. <a href="/wiki/Classical_albedo_features_on_Mars" title="Classical albedo features on Mars">Albedo features</a> are named for classical mythology. Craters larger than roughly 50&#160;km are named for deceased scientists and writers and others who have contributed to the study of Mars. Smaller craters are named for towns and villages of the world with populations of less than 100,000. Large valleys are named for the word "Mars" or "star" in various languages; smaller valleys are named for rivers.<sup id="cite_ref-usgs_153-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-usgs-153">&#91;152&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Large <a href="/wiki/Albedo" title="Albedo">albedo</a> features retain many of the older names but are often updated to reflect new knowledge of the nature of the features. For example, <i>Nix Olympica</i> (the snows of Olympus) has become <i><a href="/wiki/Olympus_Mons" title="Olympus Mons">Olympus Mons</a></i> (Mount Olympus).<sup id="cite_ref-viking_1950_2000_154-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-viking_1950_2000-154">&#91;153&#93;</a></sup> The surface of Mars as seen from Earth is divided into two kinds of areas, with differing albedo. The paler plains covered with dust and sand rich in reddish iron oxides were once thought of as Martian "continents" and given names like <a href="/wiki/Arabia_Terra" title="Arabia Terra">Arabia Terra</a> (<i>land of Arabia</i>) or <a href="/wiki/Amazonis_Planitia" title="Amazonis Planitia">Amazonis Planitia</a> (<i>Amazonian plain</i>). The dark features were thought to be seas, hence their names <a href="/wiki/Mare_Erythraeum" title="Mare Erythraeum">Mare Erythraeum</a>, Mare Sirenum and <a href="/wiki/Aurorae_Sinus" title="Aurorae Sinus">Aurorae Sinus</a>. The largest dark feature seen from Earth is <a href="/wiki/Syrtis_Major_Planum" title="Syrtis Major Planum">Syrtis Major Planum</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> The permanent northern polar ice cap is named <a href="/wiki/Planum_Boreum" title="Planum Boreum">Planum Boreum</a>. The southern cap is called <a href="/wiki/Planum_Australe" title="Planum Australe">Planum Australe</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars's equator is defined by its rotation, but the location of its <a href="/wiki/Prime_Meridian" class="mw-redirect" title="Prime Meridian">Prime Meridian</a> was specified, as was Earth's (at <a href="/wiki/Greenwich" title="Greenwich">Greenwich</a>), by choice of an arbitrary point; Mädler and Beer selected a line for their first maps of Mars in 1830. After the spacecraft <i><a href="/wiki/Mariner_9" title="Mariner 9">Mariner 9</a></i> provided extensive imagery of Mars in 1972, a small crater (later called <a href="/wiki/Airy-0" title="Airy-0">Airy-0</a>), located in the <a href="/wiki/Sinus_Meridiani" title="Sinus Meridiani">Sinus Meridiani</a> ("Middle Bay" or "Meridian Bay"), was chosen by <a href="/wiki/Merton_Davies" class="mw-redirect" title="Merton Davies">Merton Davies</a>, <a href="/wiki/Harold_Masursky" title="Harold Masursky">Harold Masursky</a>, and <a href="/wiki/G%C3%A9rard_de_Vaucouleurs" title="Gérard de Vaucouleurs">Gérard de Vaucouleurs</a> for the definition of 0.0° longitude to coincide with the original selection.<sup id="cite_ref-157" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-157">&#91;156&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-archinal_caplinger_158-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-archinal_caplinger-158">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-159" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159">&#91;158&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Because Mars has no oceans and hence no "<a href="/wiki/Sea_level" title="Sea level">sea level</a>", a zero-elevation surface had to be selected as a reference level; this is called the <i><a href="/wiki/Areoid" class="mw-redirect" title="Areoid">areoid</a></i><sup id="cite_ref-NASAMola2007_160-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASAMola2007-160">&#91;159&#93;</a></sup> of Mars, analogous to the terrestrial <a href="/wiki/Geoid" title="Geoid">geoid</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ArdalanKarimi2009_161-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ArdalanKarimi2009-161">&#91;160&#93;</a></sup> Zero altitude was defined by the height at which there is 610.5&#160;<a href="/wiki/Pascal_(unit)" title="Pascal (unit)">Pa</a> (6.105&#160;<a href="/wiki/Bar_(unit)" title="Bar (unit)">mbar</a>) of atmospheric pressure.<sup id="cite_ref-pers66_162-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pers66-162">&#91;161&#93;</a></sup> This pressure corresponds to the <a href="/wiki/Triple_point" title="Triple point">triple point</a> of water, and it is about 0.6% of the sea level surface pressure on Earth (0.006 atm).<sup id="cite_ref-lunine99_163-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lunine99-163">&#91;162&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>For mapping purposes, the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Geological_Survey" title="United States Geological Survey">United States Geological Survey</a> divides the surface of Mars into <a href="/wiki/List_of_quadrangles_on_Mars" title="List of quadrangles on Mars">thirty cartographic quadrangles</a>, each named for a classical albedo feature it contains.<sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">&#91;163&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Volcanoes">Volcanoes</span></h4>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Volcanology_of_Mars" class="mw-redirect" title="Volcanology of Mars">Volcanology of Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg/220px-Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="205" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg/330px-Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg/440px-Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2020" data-file-height="1883" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Olympus_Mons_alt.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="/wiki/Viking_1" title="Viking 1">Viking 1</a></i> image of <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Mons" title="Olympus Mons">Olympus Mons</a>. The volcano and related terrain are approximately 550&#160;km (340&#160;mi) across.</div></div></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Shield_volcano" title="Shield volcano">shield volcano</a> <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Mons" title="Olympus Mons">Olympus Mons</a> (<i>Mount Olympus</i>) is an extinct volcano in the vast upland region <a href="/wiki/Tharsis" title="Tharsis">Tharsis</a>, which contains several other large volcanoes. The edifice is over 600&#160;km (370&#160;mi) wide.<sup id="cite_ref-165" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-165">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Plescia04_166-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Plescia04-166">&#91;165&#93;</a></sup> Because the mountain is so large, with complex structure at its edges, allocating a height to it is difficult. Its local relief, from the foot of the cliffs which form its northwest margin to its peak, is over 21&#160;km (13&#160;mi),<sup id="cite_ref-Plescia04_166-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Plescia04-166">&#91;165&#93;</a></sup> a little over twice the height of <a href="/wiki/Mauna_Kea" title="Mauna Kea">Mauna Kea</a> as measured from its base on the ocean floor. The total elevation change from the plains of <a href="/wiki/Amazonis_Planitia" title="Amazonis Planitia">Amazonis Planitia</a>, over 1,000&#160;km (620&#160;mi) to the northwest, to the summit approaches 26&#160;km (16&#160;mi),<sup id="cite_ref-Comins_167-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Comins-167">&#91;166&#93;</a></sup> roughly three times the height of <a href="/wiki/Mount_Everest" title="Mount Everest">Mount Everest</a>, which in comparison stands at just over 8.8 kilometres (5.5&#160;mi). Consequently, Olympus Mons is either the <a href="/wiki/List_of_tallest_mountains_in_the_Solar_System" title="List of tallest mountains in the Solar System">tallest or second-tallest mountain in the Solar System</a>; the only known mountain which might be taller is the <a href="/wiki/Rheasilvia" title="Rheasilvia">Rheasilvia</a> peak on the asteroid <a href="/wiki/4_Vesta" title="4 Vesta">Vesta</a>, at 20–25&#160;km (12–16&#160;mi).<sup id="cite_ref-Schenk2012_168-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Schenk2012-168">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Impact_topography">Impact topography</span></h4>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Martian_dichotomy" title="Martian dichotomy">dichotomy</a> of Martian topography is striking: northern plains flattened by lava flows contrast with the southern highlands, pitted and cratered by ancient impacts. It is possible that, four billion years ago, the Northern Hemisphere of Mars was struck by an object one-tenth to two-thirds the size of Earth's <a href="/wiki/Moon" title="Moon">Moon</a>.
