If this is the case, the Northern Hemisphere of Mars would be the site of an <a href="/wiki/Impact_crater" title="Impact crater">impact crater</a> 10,600 by 8,500 kilometres (6,600 by 5,300&#160;mi) in size, or roughly the area of Europe, Asia, and Australia combined, surpassing <a href="/wiki/Utopia_Planitia" title="Utopia Planitia">Utopia Planitia</a> and the Moon's <a href="/wiki/South_Pole%E2%80%93Aitken_basin" title="South Pole–Aitken basin">South Pole–Aitken basin</a> as the largest impact crater in the Solar System.<sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">&#91;168&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:6_170-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:6-170">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-171" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">&#91;170&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars is scarred by a number of impact craters: a total of 43,000 craters with a diameter of 5 kilometres (3.1&#160;mi) or greater have been found.<sup id="cite_ref-wright03_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wright03-172">&#91;171&#93;</a></sup> The largest exposed crater is <a href="/wiki/Hellas_Planitia" title="Hellas Planitia">Hellas</a>, which is 2,300 kilometres (1,400&#160;mi) wide and 7,000 metres (23,000&#160;ft) deep, and is a light <a href="/wiki/Albedo_feature" title="Albedo feature">albedo feature</a> clearly visible from Earth.<sup id="cite_ref-173" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-173">&#91;172&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-174" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-174">&#91;173&#93;</a></sup> There are other notable impact features, such as <a href="/wiki/Argyre_Planitia" title="Argyre Planitia">Argyre</a>, which is around 1,800 kilometres (1,100&#160;mi) in diameter,<sup id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-175">&#91;174&#93;</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Isidis_Planitia" title="Isidis Planitia">Isidis</a>, which is around 1,500 kilometres (930&#160;mi) in diameter.<sup id="cite_ref-176" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-176">&#91;175&#93;</a></sup> Due to the smaller mass and size of Mars, the probability of an object colliding with the planet is about half that of Earth. Mars is located closer to the <a href="/wiki/Asteroid_belt" title="Asteroid belt">asteroid belt</a>, so it has an increased chance of being struck by materials from that source. Mars is more likely to be struck by short-period <a href="/wiki/Comet" title="Comet">comets</a>, <i>i.e.</i>, those that lie within the orbit of <a href="/wiki/Jupiter" title="Jupiter">Jupiter</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-emp9_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-emp9-177">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Martian craters can have a morphology that suggests the ground became wet after the meteor impacted.<sup id="cite_ref-emp45_178-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-emp45-178">&#91;177&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Tectonic_sites">Tectonic sites</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg/220px-Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg" decoding="async" width="220" height="220" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg/330px-Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg/440px-Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg 2x" data-file-width="1552" data-file-height="1552" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_Valles_Marineris.jpeg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Valles_Marineris" title="Valles Marineris">Valles Marineris</a>, taken by the <i><a href="/wiki/Viking_1" title="Viking 1">Viking 1</a></i> probe</div></div></div>
<p>The large canyon, <a href="/wiki/Valles_Marineris" title="Valles Marineris">Valles Marineris</a> (Latin for "<a href="/wiki/Mariner_program" title="Mariner program">Mariner</a> Valleys", also known as Agathodaemon in the old canal maps<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">&#91;178&#93;</a></sup>), has a length of 4,000 kilometres (2,500&#160;mi) and a depth of up to 7 kilometres (4.3&#160;mi). The length of Valles Marineris is equivalent to the length of Europe and extends across one-fifth the circumference of Mars. By comparison, the <a href="/wiki/Grand_Canyon" title="Grand Canyon">Grand Canyon</a> on Earth is only 446 kilometres (277&#160;mi) long and nearly 2 kilometres (1.2&#160;mi) deep. Valles Marineris was formed due to the swelling of the Tharsis area, which caused the crust in the area of Valles Marineris to collapse. In 2012, it was proposed that Valles Marineris is not just a <a href="/wiki/Graben" title="Graben">graben</a>, but a plate boundary where 150 kilometres (93&#160;mi) of <a href="/wiki/Transform_fault" title="Transform fault">transverse motion</a> has occurred, making Mars a planet with possibly a two-<a href="/wiki/Tectonic_plate" class="mw-redirect" title="Tectonic plate">tectonic plate</a> arrangement.<sup id="cite_ref-tectonic_180-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tectonic-180">&#91;179&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Lin,_An_181-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lin,_An-181">&#91;180&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Holes_and_caves">Holes and caves</span></h4>
<p>Images from the <a href="/wiki/Thermal_Emission_Imaging_System" title="Thermal Emission Imaging System">Thermal Emission Imaging System</a> (THEMIS) aboard NASA's <a href="/wiki/2001_Mars_Odyssey" title="2001 Mars Odyssey">Mars Odyssey orbiter</a> have revealed seven possible <a href="/wiki/Cave" title="Cave">cave</a> entrances on the flanks of the volcano <a href="/wiki/Arsia_Mons" title="Arsia Mons">Arsia Mons</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cushing_titus_wynn07_182-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cushing_titus_wynn07-182">&#91;181&#93;</a></sup> The caves, named after loved ones of their discoverers, are collectively known as the "seven sisters".<sup id="cite_ref-nau070328_183-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nau070328-183">&#91;182&#93;</a></sup> Cave entrances measure from 100 to 252 metres (328 to 827&#160;ft) wide and they are estimated to be at least 73 to 96 metres (240 to 315&#160;ft) deep. Because light does not reach the floor of most of the caves, they may extend much deeper than these lower estimates and widen below the surface. "Dena" is the only exception; its floor is visible and was measured to be 130 metres (430&#160;ft) deep. The interiors of these caverns may be protected from micrometeoroids, UV radiation, <a href="/wiki/Solar_flare" title="Solar flare">solar flares</a> and high energy particles that bombard the planet's surface.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc070317_184-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc070317-184">&#91;183&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-185" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-185">&#91;184&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Atmosphere">Atmosphere</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Mars" title="Atmosphere of Mars">Atmosphere of Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_atmosphere.jpg" class="image"><img alt="see caption" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Mars_atmosphere.jpg/220px-Mars_atmosphere.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="246" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Mars_atmosphere.jpg/330px-Mars_atmosphere.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Mars_atmosphere.jpg/440px-Mars_atmosphere.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1205" data-file-height="1349" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_atmosphere.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Edge-on view of Mars atmosphere by <i>Viking 1</i> probe</div></div></div>
<p>Mars lost its <a href="/wiki/Magnetosphere" title="Magnetosphere">magnetosphere</a> 4&#160;billion years ago,<sup id="cite_ref-swind_186-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-swind-186">&#91;185&#93;</a></sup> possibly because of numerous asteroid strikes,<sup id="cite_ref-187" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-187">&#91;186&#93;</a></sup> so the <a href="/wiki/Solar_wind" title="Solar wind">solar wind</a> interacts directly with the Martian <a href="/wiki/Ionosphere" title="Ionosphere">ionosphere</a>, lowering the atmospheric density by <a href="/wiki/Atmospheric_stripping" class="mw-redirect" title="Atmospheric stripping">stripping</a> away atoms from the outer layer.<sup id="cite_ref-:7_188-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-188">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup> Both <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Global_Surveyor" title="Mars Global Surveyor">Mars Global Surveyor</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Express" title="Mars Express">Mars Express</a></i> have detected ionised atmospheric particles trailing off into space behind Mars,<sup id="cite_ref-swind_186-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-swind-186">&#91;185&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-swind2_189-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-swind2-189">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup> and this atmospheric loss is being studied by the <a href="/wiki/MAVEN" title="MAVEN">MAVEN</a> orbiter. Compared to Earth, the <a href="/wiki/Celestial_body_atmosphere" class="mw-redirect" title="Celestial body atmosphere">atmosphere</a> of Mars is quite rarefied. <a href="/wiki/Atmospheric_pressure" title="Atmospheric pressure">Atmospheric pressure</a> on the surface today ranges from a low of 30&#160;<a href="/wiki/Pascal_(unit)" title="Pascal (unit)">Pa</a> (0.0044&#160;<a href="/wiki/Pound_per_square_inch" title="Pound per square inch">psi</a>) on <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Mons" title="Olympus Mons">Olympus Mons</a> to over 1,155&#160;Pa (0.1675&#160;psi) in <a href="/wiki/Hellas_Planitia" title="Hellas Planitia">Hellas Planitia</a>, with a mean pressure at the surface level of 600&#160;Pa (0.087&#160;psi).<sup id="cite_ref-bolonkin09_190-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bolonkin09-190">&#91;189&#93;</a></sup> The highest atmospheric density on Mars is equal to that found 35 kilometres (22&#160;mi)<sup id="cite_ref-atkinson07_191-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-atkinson07-191">&#91;190&#93;</a></sup> above Earth's surface. The resulting mean surface pressure is only 0.6% of that of Earth  101.3&#160;kPa (14.69&#160;psi). The <a href="/wiki/Scale_height" title="Scale height">scale height</a> of the atmosphere is about 10.8 kilometres (6.7&#160;mi),<sup id="cite_ref-carr06_192-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-carr06-192">&#91;191&#93;</a></sup> which is higher than Earth's 6 kilometres (3.7&#160;mi), because the surface <a href="/wiki/Gravity_of_Mars" title="Gravity of Mars">gravity of Mars</a> is only about 38% of Earth's.<sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">&#91;192&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>
The atmosphere of Mars consists of about 96% <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">carbon dioxide</a>, 1.93% <a href="/wiki/Argon" title="Argon">argon</a> and 1.89% <a href="/wiki/Nitrogen" title="Nitrogen">nitrogen</a> along with traces of <a href="/wiki/Oxygen" title="Oxygen">oxygen</a> and water.<sup id="cite_ref-NasaFactSheet_2-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NasaFactSheet-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Abundance_194-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Abundance-194">&#91;193&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:7_188-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-188">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup> The atmosphere is quite dusty, containing particulates about 1.5 <a href="/wiki/%CE%9Cm" class="mw-redirect" title="Μm">µm</a> in diameter which give the Martian sky a <a href="/wiki/Tawny_(color)" title="Tawny (color)">tawny</a> color when seen from the surface.<sup id="cite_ref-dusty_195-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dusty-195">&#91;194&#93;</a></sup> It may take on a <a href="/wiki/Pink" title="Pink">pink</a> hue due to <a href="/wiki/Iron_oxide" title="Iron oxide">iron oxide</a> particles suspended in it.<sup id="cite_ref-Rees2012_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rees2012-28">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> The concentration of <a href="/wiki/Methane_on_Mars" class="mw-redirect" title="Methane on Mars">methane in the Martian atmosphere</a> fluctuates from about 0.24 <a href="/wiki/Parts_per_billion" class="mw-redirect" title="Parts per billion">ppb</a> during the northern winter to about 0.65 ppb during the summer.<sup id="cite_ref-Sample2018_196-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sample2018-196">&#91;195&#93;</a></sup> Estimates of its lifetime range from 0.6 to 4 years,<sup id="cite_ref-plumes_197-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plumes-197">&#91;196&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nature460_198-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nature460-198">&#91;197&#93;</a></sup> so its presence indicates that an active source of the gas must be present. Methane could be produced by non-biological process such as <a href="/wiki/Serpentinite" title="Serpentinite">serpentinization</a> involving water, carbon dioxide, and the mineral <a href="/wiki/Olivine" title="Olivine">olivine</a>, which is known to be common on Mars,<sup id="cite_ref-olivine_199-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-olivine-199">&#91;198&#93;</a></sup> or by Martian life.<sup id="cite_ref-200" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-200">&#91;199&#93;</a></sup></p><div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg/300px-PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg" decoding="async" width="300" height="119" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg/450px-PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg/600px-PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5170" data-file-height="2045" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA18613-MarsMAVEN-Atmosphere-3UV-Views-20141014.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Mars" title="Atmosphere of Mars">Escaping atmosphere</a> on Mars (<a href="/wiki/Carbon" title="Carbon">carbon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Oxygen" title="Oxygen">oxygen</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen" title="Hydrogen">hydrogen</a>) by <a href="/wiki/MAVEN" title="MAVEN">MAVEN</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ultraviolet%E2%80%93visible_spectroscopy" title="Ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy">UV</a><sup id="cite_ref-NASA-20141014-NJ_201-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA-20141014-NJ-201">&#91;200&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>
<p>Compared to Earth, its higher concentration of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> and lower surface pressure may be why sound is attenuated more on Mars, where natural sources are rare apart from the wind. Using acoustic recordings collected by the <i>Perseverance</i> rover, researchers concluded that the speed of sound there is approximately 240&#160;m/s for frequencies below 240&#160;Hz, and 250&#160;m/s for those above.<sup id="cite_ref-202" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-202">&#91;201&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-203" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-203">&#91;202&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Aurora_on_Mars" title="Aurora on Mars">Auroras</a> have been detected on Mars.<sup id="cite_ref-204" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-204">&#91;203&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-205" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-205">&#91;204&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NASA-20150318_206-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA-20150318-206">&#91;205&#93;</a></sup> Because Mars lacks a global magnetic field, the types and distribution of auroras there differ from those on Earth;<sup id="cite_ref-207" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-207">&#91;206&#93;</a></sup> rather than being mostly restricted to polar regions as is the case on Earth, a Martian aurora can encompass the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-:8_208-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:8-208">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup> In September 2017, NASA reported <a href="/wiki/Radiation" title="Radiation">radiation</a> levels on the surface of the planet Mars were temporarily <a href="/wiki/Orders_of_magnitude_(radiation)" title="Orders of magnitude (radiation)">doubled</a>, and were associated with an <a href="/wiki/Aurora" title="Aurora">aurora</a> 25 times brighter than any observed earlier, due to a massive, and unexpected, <a href="/wiki/Coronal_mass_ejection" title="Coronal mass ejection">solar storm</a> in the middle of the month.<sup id="cite_ref-:8_208-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:8-208">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nasa20170929_209-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa20170929-209">&#91;208&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Climate">Climate</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Climate_of_Mars" title="Climate of Mars">Climate of Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Dust_storm_co.tif" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Dust_storm_co.tif/lossy-page1-220px-Dust_storm_co.tif.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="82" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Dust_storm_co.tif/lossy-page1-330px-Dust_storm_co.tif.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Dust_storm_co.tif/lossy-page1-440px-Dust_storm_co.tif.jpg 2x" data-file-width="9614" data-file-height="3600" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Dust_storm_co.tif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Detail of a Marsian dust storm, as viewed from orbit</div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg/220px-PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="117" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg/330px-PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg/440px-PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="852" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA03170_fig1duststroms.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Mars without a dust storm in June 2001 (on left) and with a global dust storm in July 2001 (on right), as seen by Mars Global Surveyor</div></div></div>
<p>Of all the planets in the Solar System, the seasons of Mars are the most Earth-like, due to the similar tilts of the two planets' rotational axes. The lengths of the Martian seasons are about twice those of Earth's because Mars's greater distance from the Sun leads to the Martian year being about two Earth years long. Martian surface temperatures vary from lows of about −110&#160;°C (−166&#160;°F) to highs of up to 35&#160;°C (95&#160;°F) in equatorial summer.<sup id="cite_ref-hot_18-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hot-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> The wide range in temperatures is due to the thin atmosphere which cannot store much solar heat, the low atmospheric pressure, and the low <a href="/wiki/Volumetric_heat_capacity" title="Volumetric heat capacity">thermal inertia</a> of Martian soil.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa_surface_210-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa_surface-210">&#91;209&#93;</a></sup> The planet is 1.52 times as far from the Sun as Earth, resulting in just 43% of the amount of sunlight.<sup id="cite_ref-disc920901_211-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-disc920901-211">&#91;210&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-212" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-212">&#91;211&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>If Mars had an Earth-like orbit, its seasons would be similar to Earth's because its <a href="/wiki/Axial_tilt" title="Axial tilt">axial tilt</a> is similar to Earth's. The comparatively large <a href="/wiki/Orbital_eccentricity" title="Orbital eccentricity">eccentricity</a> of the Martian orbit has a significant effect. Mars is near <a href="/wiki/Apsis" title="Apsis">perihelion</a> when it is summer in the Southern Hemisphere and winter in the north, and near <a href="/wiki/Apsis" title="Apsis">aphelion</a> when it is winter in the Southern Hemisphere and summer in the north. As a result, the seasons in the Southern Hemisphere are more extreme and the seasons in the northern are milder than would otherwise be the case. The summer temperatures in the south can be warmer than the equivalent summer temperatures in the north by up to 30&#160;°C (54&#160;°F).<sup id="cite_ref-goodman97_213-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-goodman97-213">&#91;212&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars has the largest <a href="/wiki/Dust_storm" title="Dust storm">dust storms</a> in the Solar System, reaching speeds of over 160&#160;km/h (100&#160;mph). These can vary from a storm over a small area, to gigantic storms that cover the entire planet. They tend to occur when Mars is closest to the Sun, and have been shown to increase the global temperature.<sup id="cite_ref-philips01_214-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-philips01-214">&#91;213&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Orbit_and_rotation">Orbit and rotation</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Orbit_of_Mars" title="Orbit of Mars">Orbit of Mars</a></div><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Timekeeping_on_Mars" title="Timekeeping on Mars">Timekeeping on Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif" class="image"><img alt="Mars circling the Sun further and slower than Earth" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif/220px-Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif/330px-Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif/440px-Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Solar_system_orrery_inner_planets.gif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Orbit of Mars and other Inner Solar System planets</div></div></div>
<p>Mars's average distance from the Sun is roughly 230&#160;million&#160;km (143&#160;million&#160;mi), and its orbital period is 687 (Earth) days. The solar day (or <a href="/wiki/Mars_sol" title="Mars sol">sol</a>) on Mars is only slightly longer than an Earth day: 24 hours, 39 minutes, and 35.244 seconds.<sup id="cite_ref-216" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-216">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup> A Martian year is equal to 1.8809 Earth years, or 1 year, 320 days, and 18.2 hours.<sup id="cite_ref-NasaFactSheet_2-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NasaFactSheet-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The axial tilt of Mars is 25.19° relative to its <a href="/wiki/Orbital_plane" title="Orbital plane">orbital plane</a>, which is similar to the axial tilt of Earth.<sup id="cite_ref-NasaFactSheet_2-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NasaFactSheet-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> As a result, Mars has seasons like Earth, though on Mars they are nearly twice as long because its orbital period is that much longer. In the present day epoch, the orientation of the <a href="/wiki/North_pole" class="mw-redirect" title="North pole">north pole</a> of Mars is close to the star <a href="/wiki/Deneb" title="Deneb">Deneb</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-barlow08_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-barlow08-21">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars has a relatively pronounced <a href="/wiki/Orbital_eccentricity" title="Orbital eccentricity">orbital eccentricity</a> of about 0.09; of the seven other planets in the Solar System, only <a href="/wiki/Mercury_(planet)" title="Mercury (planet)">Mercury</a> has a larger orbital eccentricity. It is known that in the past, Mars has had a much more circular orbit. At one point, 1.35&#160;million Earth years ago, Mars had an eccentricity of roughly 0.002, much less than that of Earth today.<sup id="cite_ref-mars_eccentricity_217-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mars_eccentricity-217">&#91;216&#93;</a></sup> Mars's <a href="/wiki/Milankovitch_cycles" title="Milankovitch cycles">cycle of eccentricity</a> is 96,000 Earth years compared to Earth's cycle of 100,000 years.<sup id="cite_ref-Meeus2003_218-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Meeus2003-218">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars approaches Earth in a <a href="/wiki/Synodic_period" class="mw-redirect" title="Synodic period">synodic period</a> of 779.94 days. Earth orbits the Sun the closest to Mars's orbit around the Sun, and Mars orbit is the second closest to Earth after the <a href="/wiki/Orbit_of_Venus" title="Orbit of Venus">orbit of Venus</a>. Therefore, their closest approaches, the <a href="/wiki/Inferior_conjunction" class="mw-redirect" title="Inferior conjunction">inferior conjunctions</a>, are the second closest for Earth after those with Venus, and the closest for Mars to any other planet. The <a href="/wiki/Gravitational_potential" title="Gravitational potential">gravitational potential</a> difference, and thus the <a href="/wiki/Delta-v_budget" title="Delta-v budget">delta-v needed</a> to <a href="/wiki/Transfer_orbit" title="Transfer orbit">transfer</a> between Mars and Earth is the second lowest for Earth and the lowest for Mars to any other planet, while transfers can possibly be optimized with Venus <a href="/wiki/Flyby_(spaceflight)" title="Flyby (spaceflight)">flybys</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Petropoulos_Longuski_Bonfiglio_2000_pp._776–783_219-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Petropoulos_Longuski_Bonfiglio_2000_pp._776–783-219">&#91;218&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Taylor_2020_220-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taylor_2020-220">&#91;219&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Habitability_and_search_for_life">Habitability and search for life</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Life_on_Mars" title="Life on Mars">Life on Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg/220px-MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="243" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg/330px-MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg/440px-MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3819" data-file-height="4223" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:MarsCuriosityRover-Drilling-Sol170%2B%2B-2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)" title="Curiosity (rover)">Curiosity</a></i> rover’s robotic arm showing drill in place, February 2013</div></div></div>
<p>During the late nineteenth century, it was widely accepted in the astronomical community that Mars had life-supporting qualities, including the presence of oxygen and water.<sup id="cite_ref-CampbellWW_221-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CampbellWW-221">&#91;220&#93;</a></sup> However, in 1894 <a href="/wiki/William_Wallace_Campbell" title="William Wallace Campbell">W. W. Campbell</a> at <a href="/wiki/Lick_Observatory" title="Lick Observatory">Lick Observatory</a> observed the planet and found that "if water vapor or oxygen occur in the atmosphere of Mars it is in quantities too small to be detected by spectroscopes then available".<sup id="cite_ref-CampbellWW_221-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CampbellWW-221">&#91;220&#93;</a></sup> That observation contradicted many of the measurements of the time and was not widely accepted.<sup id="cite_ref-CampbellWW_221-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CampbellWW-221">&#91;220&#93;</a></sup> Campbell and <a href="/wiki/Vesto_Slipher" class="mw-redirect" title="Vesto Slipher">V. M. Slipher</a> repeated the study in 1909 using better instruments, but with the same results. It wasn't until the findings were confirmed by <a href="/wiki/Walter_Sydney_Adams" title="Walter Sydney Adams">W. S. Adams</a> in 1925 that the myth of the Earth-like habitability of Mars was finally broken.<sup id="cite_ref-CampbellWW_221-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CampbellWW-221">&#91;220&#93;</a></sup> However, even in the 1960s, articles were published on Martian biology, putting aside explanations other than life for the seasonal changes on Mars. Detailed scenarios for the metabolism and chemical cycles for a functional ecosystem were being published as late as 1962.<sup id="cite_ref-science136_3510_222-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-science136_3510-222">&#91;221&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The current understanding of <a href="/wiki/Planetary_habitability" title="Planetary habitability">planetary habitability</a>&#160;&#8211;&#32;the ability of a world to develop environmental conditions favorable to the emergence of life&#160;&#8211;&#32;favors planets that have liquid water on their surface. Most often this requires the orbit of a planet to lie within the <a href="/wiki/Circumstellar_habitable_zone" title="Circumstellar habitable zone">habitable zone</a>, which for the Sun is estimated to extend from within the orbit of Earth to about that of Mars.<sup id="cite_ref-Kopparapu2013b_223-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kopparapu2013b-223">&#91;222&#93;</a></sup> During perihelion, Mars dips inside this region, but Mars's thin (low-pressure) atmosphere prevents liquid water from existing over large regions for extended periods. The past flow of liquid water demonstrates the planet's potential for habitability. Recent evidence has suggested that any water on the Martian surface may have been too salty and acidic to support regular terrestrial life.<sup id="cite_ref-saltlife_224-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-saltlife-224">&#91;223&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The environmental conditions on Mars are a challenge to sustaining organic life: the planet has little <a href="/wiki/Heat_transfer" title="Heat transfer">heat transfer</a> across its surface, it has poor insulation against <a href="/wiki/Solar_wind#Atmospheres" title="Solar wind">bombardment</a> by the <a href="/wiki/Solar_wind" title="Solar wind">solar wind</a> due to the absence of a magnetosphere and has insufficient atmospheric pressure to retain water in a liquid form (water instead <a href="/wiki/Sublimation_(phase_transition)" title="Sublimation (phase transition)">sublimes</a> to a gaseous state). Mars is nearly, or perhaps totally, geologically dead; the end of volcanic activity has apparently stopped the recycling of chemicals and minerals between the surface and interior of the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-hannsson97_225-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hannsson97-225">&#91;224&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg" class="image"><img alt="see caption" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg/300px-PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg" decoding="async" width="300" height="119" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg/450px-PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg/600px-PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3020" data-file-height="1200" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:PIA16226-MarsCuriosityRover-FirstScoopOfSoil-20121007.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Scoop of Mars soil by <i>Curiosity</i>, October 2012</div></div></div>
<p><i>In situ</i> investigations have been performed on Mars by the <a href="/wiki/Viking_landers" class="mw-redirect" title="Viking landers"><i>Viking</i> landers</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Spirit_(rover)" title="Spirit (rover)">Spirit</a></i> and <i>Opportunity</i> rovers, <i><a href="/wiki/Phoenix_(spacecraft)" title="Phoenix (spacecraft)">Phoenix</a></i> lander, and <i>Curiosity</i> rover. Evidence suggests that the planet was once significantly more habitable than it is today, but whether living <a href="/wiki/Organism" title="Organism">organisms</a> ever existed there remains unknown. The <a href="/wiki/Viking_probes" class="mw-redirect" title="Viking probes"><i>Viking</i> probes</a> of the mid-1970s carried experiments designed to detect microorganisms in Martian soil at their respective landing sites and had positive results, including a temporary increase of <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1123817410">.mw-parser-output .template-chem2-su{display:inline-block;font-size:80%;line-height:1;vertical-align:-0.35em}.mw-parser-output .template-chem2-su>span{display:block;text-align:left}.mw-parser-output sub.template-chem2-sub{font-size:80%;vertical-align:-0.35em}.mw-parser-output sup.template-chem2-sup{font-size:80%;vertical-align:0.65em}</style><span class="chemf nowrap">CO<sub class="template-chem2-sub">2</sub></span> production on exposure to water and nutrients. This sign of life was later disputed by scientists, resulting in a continuing debate, with NASA scientist <a href="/wiki/Gilbert_Levin" title="Gilbert Levin">Gilbert Levin</a> asserting that <i>Viking</i> may have found life.<sup id="cite_ref-nytobit_226-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nytobit-226">&#91;225&#93;</a></sup> Tests conducted by the <i>Phoenix Mars</i> lander have shown that the soil has an <a href="/wiki/Alkaline" class="mw-redirect" title="Alkaline">alkaline</a> <a href="/wiki/PH" title="PH">pH</a> and it contains magnesium, sodium, potassium and chloride.<sup id="cite_ref-nutrient_227-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nutrient-227">&#91;226&#93;</a></sup> The soil nutrients may be able to support life, but life would still have to be shielded from the intense ultraviolet light.<sup id="cite_ref-UV_228-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UV-228">&#91;227&#93;</a></sup> A 2014 analysis of Martian meteorite EETA79001 found <a href="/wiki/Chlorate" title="Chlorate">chlorate</a>, <a href="/wiki/Perchlorate" title="Perchlorate">perchlorate</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Nitrate" title="Nitrate">nitrate</a> ions in sufficiently high concentration to suggest that they are widespread on Mars. UV and X-ray radiation would turn chlorate and perchlorate ions into other, highly <a href="/wiki/Redox" title="Redox">reactive</a> <a href="/wiki/Oxyanion" title="Oxyanion">oxychlorines</a>, indicating that any organic molecules would have to be buried under the surface to survive.<sup id="cite_ref-229" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-229">&#91;228&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Scientists have proposed that carbonate globules found in <a href="/wiki/Meteorite" title="Meteorite">meteorite</a> <a href="/wiki/Allan_Hills_84001" title="Allan Hills 84001">ALH84001</a>, which is thought to have originated from Mars, could be fossilized microbes extant on Mars when the meteorite was blasted from the Martian surface by a meteor strike some 15&#160;million years ago. This proposal has been met with skepticism, and an exclusively inorganic origin for the shapes has been proposed.<sup id="cite_ref-am89_230-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-am89-230">&#91;229&#93;</a></sup> Small quantities of <a href="/wiki/Methane" title="Methane">methane</a> and <a href="/wiki/Formaldehyde" title="Formaldehyde">formaldehyde</a> detected by Mars orbiters are both claimed to be possible evidence for life, as these <a href="/wiki/Chemical_compound" title="Chemical compound">chemical compounds</a> would quickly break down in the Martian atmosphere.<sup id="cite_ref-icarus172_231-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-icarus172-231">&#91;230&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-form_232-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-form-232">&#91;231&#93;</a></sup> Alternatively, these compounds may instead be replenished by volcanic or other geological means, such as <a href="/wiki/Serpentinite" title="Serpentinite">serpentinite</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-olivine_199-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-olivine-199">&#91;198&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Impactite" title="Impactite">Impact glass</a>, formed by the impact of meteors, which on Earth can preserve signs of life, has also been found on the surface of the impact craters on Mars.<sup id="cite_ref-brown20140418_233-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-brown20140418-233">&#91;232&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Schultz2014_234-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Schultz2014-234">&#91;233&#93;</a></sup> Likewise, the glass in impact craters on Mars could have preserved signs of life, if life existed at the site.<sup id="cite_ref-nasapr20150608_235-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasapr20150608-235">&#91;234&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-brown20150608_236-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-brown20150608-236">&#91;235&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sciam20150612_237-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sciam20150612-237">&#91;236&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Moons">Moons</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Moons_of_Mars" title="Moons of Mars">Moons of Mars</a>, <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(moon)" title="Phobos (moon)">Phobos (moon)</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(moon)" title="Deimos (moon)">Deimos (moon)</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1096954695/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"/><div class="thumb tmulti tleft"><div class="thumbinner multiimageinner" style="width:342px;max-width:342px"><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:174px;max-width:174px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:162px;overflow:hidden"><a href="/wiki/File:Phobos_colour_2008.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Phobos_colour_2008.jpg/172px-Phobos_colour_2008.jpg" decoding="async" width="172" height="162" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Phobos_colour_2008.jpg/258px-Phobos_colour_2008.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Phobos_colour_2008.jpg/344px-Phobos_colour_2008.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3500" data-file-height="3300" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">Enhanced-color HiRISE image of <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(moon)" title="Phobos (moon)">Phobos</a>, showing a series of mostly parallel grooves and <a href="/wiki/Crater_chain" title="Crater chain">crater chains</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Stickney_(crater)" title="Stickney (crater)">Stickney crater</a> at right</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:164px;max-width:164px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:162px;overflow:hidden"><a href="/wiki/File:Deimos-MRO.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Deimos-MRO.jpg/162px-Deimos-MRO.jpg" decoding="async" width="162" height="162" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Deimos-MRO.jpg/243px-Deimos-MRO.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Deimos-MRO.jpg/324px-Deimos-MRO.jpg 2x" data-file-width="592" data-file-height="592" /></a></div><div class="thumbcaption">Enhanced-color HiRISE image of <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(moon)" title="Deimos (moon)">Deimos</a> (not to scale), showing its smooth blanket of <a href="/wiki/Regolith" title="Regolith">regolith</a></div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Mars has two relatively small (compared to Earth's) natural moons, <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(moon)" title="Phobos (moon)">Phobos</a> (about 22 kilometres (14&#160;mi) in diameter) and <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(moon)" title="Deimos (moon)">Deimos</a> (about 12 kilometres (7.5&#160;mi) in diameter), which orbit close to the planet. The origin of both moons is unclear, although a popular theory states that they were asteroids captured into Martian orbit.<sup id="cite_ref-esa31031_238-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-esa31031-238">&#91;237&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Both satellites were discovered in 1877 by <a href="/wiki/Asaph_Hall" title="Asaph Hall">Asaph Hall</a> and were named after the characters <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(mythology)" title="Phobos (mythology)">Phobos</a> (the deity of panic and fear) and <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(mythology)" class="mw-redirect" title="Deimos (mythology)">Deimos</a> (the deity of terror and dread), twins from <a href="/wiki/Greek_mythology" title="Greek mythology">Greek mythology</a> who accompanied their father <a href="/wiki/Ares" title="Ares">Ares</a>, god of war, into battle.<sup id="cite_ref-239" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-239">&#91;238&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Mars_(mythology)" title="Mars (mythology)">Mars</a> was the Roman equivalent to Ares. In modern <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>, the planet retains its ancient name <i>Ares</i> (Aris: <i>Άρης</i>).<sup id="cite_ref-:6_170-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:6-170">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From the surface of Mars, the motions of Phobos and Deimos appear different from that of the Earth's satellite, the <a href="/wiki/Moon" title="Moon">Moon</a>. Phobos rises in the west, sets in the east, and rises again in just 11 hours. Deimos, being only just outside <a href="/wiki/Synchronous_orbit" title="Synchronous orbit">synchronous orbit</a>&#160;&#8211;&#32;where the orbital period would match the planet's period of rotation&#160;&#8211;&#32;rises as expected in the east, but slowly. Because the orbit of Phobos is below synchronous altitude, <a href="/wiki/Tidal_force" title="Tidal force">tidal forces</a> from Mars are gradually lowering its orbit. In about 50&#160;million years, it could either crash into Mars's surface or break up into a ring structure around the planet.<sup id="cite_ref-240" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-240">&#91;239&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The origin of the two satellites is not well understood. Their low albedo and <a href="/wiki/Carbonaceous_chondrite" title="Carbonaceous chondrite">carbonaceous chondrite</a> composition have been regarded as similar to asteroids, supporting a capture theory. The unstable orbit of Phobos would seem to point toward a relatively recent capture. But both have <a href="/wiki/Circular_orbit" title="Circular orbit">circular orbits</a>, near the equator that is unusual for captured objects and the required capture dynamics are complex. Accretion early in the history of Mars is plausible, but would not account for a composition resembling asteroids rather than Mars itself, if that is confirmed.<sup id="cite_ref-241" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-241">&#91;240&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>A third possibility for their origin as satellites of Mars is the involvement of a third body or a type of impact disruption. More-recent lines of evidence for Phobos having a highly porous interior,<sup id="cite_ref-Andert_242-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Andert-242">&#91;241&#93;</a></sup> and suggesting a composition containing mainly <a href="/wiki/Phyllosilicates" class="mw-redirect" title="Phyllosilicates">phyllosilicates</a> and other minerals known from Mars,<sup id="cite_ref-Giuranna_243-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Giuranna-243">&#91;242&#93;</a></sup> point toward an origin of Phobos from material ejected by an impact on Mars that reaccreted in Martian orbit, similar to the <a href="/wiki/Giant_impact_hypothesis" class="mw-redirect" title="Giant impact hypothesis">prevailing theory</a> for the origin of Earth's satellite. Although the <a href="/wiki/Visible_and_near-infrared" class="mw-redirect" title="Visible and near-infrared">visible and near-infrared</a> (VNIR) spectra of the moons of Mars resemble those of outer-belt asteroids, the <a href="/wiki/Thermal_infrared" class="mw-redirect" title="Thermal infrared">thermal infrared</a> spectra of Phobos are reported to be inconsistent with <a href="/wiki/Chondrite" title="Chondrite">chondrites</a> of any class.<sup id="cite_ref-Giuranna_243-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Giuranna-243">&#91;242&#93;</a></sup> It is also possible that Phobos and Deimos are fragments of an older moon, formed by debris from a large impact on Mars, and then destroyed by a more recent impact upon the satellite.<sup id="cite_ref-244" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-244">&#91;243&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars may have yet-undiscovered moons, smaller than 50 to 100 metres (160 to 330&#160;ft) in diameter, and a dust ring is predicted to exist between Phobos and Deimos.<sup id="cite_ref-adler_245-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-adler-245">&#91;244&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Exploration">Exploration</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Exploration_of_Mars" title="Exploration of Mars">Exploration of Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_(51103361344).jpg" class="image"><img alt="see caption" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_%2851103361344%29.jpg/220px-Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_%2851103361344%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_%2851103361344%29.jpg/330px-Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_%2851103361344%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_%2851103361344%29.jpg/440px-Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_%2851103361344%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2554" data-file-height="1914" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars2020_Sol_47_-_NavRight_(51103361344).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Ingenuity_(helicopter)" title="Ingenuity (helicopter)"><i>Ingenuity</i> helicopter</a> on Mars, preparing for its first flight, April 2021</div></div></div>
<p>Dozens of crewless <a href="/wiki/Spacecraft" title="Spacecraft">spacecraft</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Orbiter" class="mw-redirect" title="Orbiter">orbiters</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mars_lander" class="mw-redirect" title="Mars lander">landers</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mars_rover" title="Mars rover">rovers</a>, have been sent to Mars by the <a href="/wiki/Soviet_space_program" title="Soviet space program">Soviet Union</a>, the <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">United States</a>, <a href="/wiki/ESA" class="mw-redirect" title="ESA">Europe</a>, <a href="/wiki/ISRO" class="mw-redirect" title="ISRO">India</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Mohammed_bin_Rashid_Space_Centre" title="Mohammed bin Rashid Space Centre">United Arab Emirates</a>, and <a href="/wiki/CNSA" class="mw-redirect" title="CNSA">China</a> to study the planet's surface, climate, and geology.<sup id="cite_ref-246" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-246">&#91;245&#93;</a></sup> NASA's <i>Mariner 4</i> was the first spacecraft to visit Mars; launched on 28 November 1964, it made its closest approach to the planet on 15 July 1965. <i>Mariner 4</i> detected the weak Martian radiation belt, measured at about 0.1% that of Earth, and captured the first images of another planet from deep space.<sup id="cite_ref-247" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-247">&#91;246&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Once <a href="/wiki/Spacecraft" title="Spacecraft">spacecraft</a> visited the planet during NASA's <a href="/wiki/Mariner_program" title="Mariner program">Mariner missions</a> in the 1960s and 1970s, many previous concepts of Mars were radically broken. After the results of the <i>Viking</i> life-detection experiments, the hypothesis of a dead planet was generally accepted.<sup id="cite_ref-ward_brownlee00_248-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ward_brownlee00-248">&#91;247&#93;</a></sup> The data from <i>Mariner 9</i> and <i>Viking</i> allowed better maps of Mars to be made, and the <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Global_Surveyor" title="Mars Global Surveyor">Mars Global Surveyor</a></i> mission, which launched in 1996 and operated until late 2006, produced complete, extremely detailed maps of the Martian topography, magnetic field and surface minerals.<sup id="cite_ref-Distant_worlds:_milestones_in_planetary_exploration_249-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Distant_worlds:_milestones_in_planetary_exploration-249">&#91;248&#93;</a></sup> These maps are available online at websites including <a href="/wiki/Google_Mars" class="mw-redirect" title="Google Mars">Google Mars</a>. Both the <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter" title="Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Express" title="Mars Express">Mars Express</a></i> continued exploring with new instruments and supporting lander missions. NASA provides two online tools: Mars Trek, which provides visualizations of the planet using data from 50 years of exploration, and <a href="/wiki/Experience_Curiosity" title="Experience Curiosity">Experience Curiosity</a>, which simulates traveling on Mars in 3-D with <i>Curiosity</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-250" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-250">&#91;249&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-251" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-251">&#91;250&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of 2023<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Mars&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, Mars is host to thirteen functioning <a href="/wiki/Spacecraft" title="Spacecraft">spacecraft</a>. Eight are in orbit<i>: <a href="/wiki/2001_Mars_Odyssey" title="2001 Mars Odyssey">2001 Mars Odyssey</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Express" title="Mars Express">Mars Express</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Mars_Reconnaissance_Orbiter" title="Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter">Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/MAVEN" title="MAVEN">MAVEN</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/ExoMars_Trace_Gas_Orbiter" class="mw-redirect" title="ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter">ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter</a></i>, the <a href="/wiki/Emirates_Mars_Mission" title="Emirates Mars Mission"><i>Hope</i></a> orbiter, and the <i><a href="/wiki/Tianwen-1" title="Tianwen-1">Tianwen-1</a></i> orbiter.<sup id="cite_ref-252" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-252">&#91;251&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-253" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-253">&#91;252&#93;</a></sup> Another five are on the surface: the <a href="/wiki/Mars_Science_Laboratory" title="Mars Science Laboratory">Mars Science Laboratory</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Curiosity_(rover)" title="Curiosity (rover)">Curiosity</a></i> rover, the <i><a href="/wiki/Perseverance_(rover)" title="Perseverance (rover)">Perseverance</a></i> rover, the <i><a href="/wiki/Ingenuity_(helicopter)" title="Ingenuity (helicopter)">Ingenuity</a></i> helicopter, the <i><a href="/wiki/Tianwen-1" title="Tianwen-1">Tianwen-1</a></i> lander, and the <i><a href="/wiki/Zhurong_(rover)" title="Zhurong (rover)">Zhurong</a></i> rover.<sup id="cite_ref-nyt-china-2021_254-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt-china-2021-254">&#91;253&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Planned missions to Mars include the <i>Rosalind Franklin</i> rover mission, designed to search for evidence of past life, which was intended to be launched in 2018 but has been repeatedly delayed, with a launch date pushed to 2024 at the earliest, with a more likely one sometime in 2028.<sup id="cite_ref-255" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-255">&#91;254&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-256" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-256">&#91;255&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-257" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-257">&#91;256&#93;</a></sup> A current concept for a joint <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a>-<a href="/wiki/European_Space_Agency" title="European Space Agency">ESA</a> mission to <a href="/wiki/NASA-ESA_Mars_Sample_Return" title="NASA-ESA Mars Sample Return">return samples from Mars</a> would launch in 2026.<sup id="cite_ref-258" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-258">&#91;257&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-259" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-259">&#91;258&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Several plans for a <a href="/wiki/Human_mission_to_Mars" title="Human mission to Mars">human mission to Mars</a> have been proposed throughout the 20th and 21st centuries, but none have come to fruition. The NASA Authorization Act of 2017 directed NASA to study the feasibility of a crewed Mars mission in the early 2030s; the resulting report eventually concluded that this would be unfeasible.<sup id="cite_ref-260" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-260">&#91;259&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-261" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-261">&#91;260&#93;</a></sup> In addition, in 2021, China was planning to send a crewed Mars mission in 2033.<sup id="cite_ref-262" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-262">&#91;261&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Private_spaceflight" title="Private spaceflight">Privately held companies</a> such as <a href="/wiki/SpaceX" title="SpaceX">SpaceX</a> have also <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Mars_program" title="SpaceX Mars program">proposed plans to send humans to Mars</a>, with the eventual goal to <a href="/wiki/Colonization_of_Mars" title="Colonization of Mars">settle on the planet</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-263" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-263">&#91;262&#93;</a></sup> The moon Phobos has been proposed as an anchor point for a <a href="/wiki/Space_elevator" title="Space elevator">space elevator</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-264" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-264">&#91;263&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Astronomy_on_Mars">Astronomy on Mars</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Astronomy_on_Mars" title="Astronomy on Mars">Astronomy on Mars</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Solar_eclipses_on_Mars" title="Solar eclipses on Mars">Solar eclipses on Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><video id="mwe_player_2" poster="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm/220px--Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm.jpg" controls="" preload="none" class="thumbimage" width="220" height="124" data-durationhint="41" data-mwtitle="Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm" data-mwprovider="wikimediacommons"><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/9/9b/Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm/Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm.480p.vp9.webm" type="video/webm; codecs=&quot;vp9, opus&quot;" data-title="VP9 (360P)" data-shorttitle="VP9 360P" data-transcodekey="360p.vp9.webm" data-width="640" data-height="360" data-bandwidth="142272" data-framerate="23.976" /><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/9/9b/Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm/Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm.360p.webm" type="video/webm; codecs=&quot;vp8, vorbis&quot;" data-title="WebM (360P)" data-shorttitle="WebM 360P" data-transcodekey="360p.webm" data-width="640" data-height="360" data-bandwidth="267768" data-framerate="23.976" /></video>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Phobos_transit_in_real_color.webm" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Phobos_(moon)" title="Phobos (moon)">Phobos</a> transits the <a href="/wiki/Sun" title="Sun">Sun</a>, as viewed by the <a href="/wiki/Perseverance_(rover)" title="Perseverance (rover)"><i>Perseverance</i> rover</a> on 2 April 2022</div></div></div>
<p>With the presence of various orbiters, landers, and rovers, it is possible to practice <a href="/wiki/Astronomy" title="Astronomy">astronomy</a> from Mars. Although Mars's moon <a href="/wiki/Phobos_(moon)" title="Phobos (moon)">Phobos</a> appears about one-third the <a href="/wiki/Angular_diameter" title="Angular diameter">angular diameter</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Full_moon" title="Full moon">full moon</a> on Earth, <a href="/wiki/Deimos_(moon)" title="Deimos (moon)">Deimos</a> appears more or less star-like, looking only slightly brighter than Venus does from Earth.<sup id="cite_ref-pl_org_deimos_265-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pl_org_deimos-265">&#91;264&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Various phenomena seen from Earth have also been observed from Mars, such as <a href="/wiki/Meteor" class="mw-redirect" title="Meteor">meteors</a> and <a href="/wiki/Aurora" title="Aurora">auroras</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-aurora_266-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-aurora-266">&#91;265&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Angular_diameter" title="Angular diameter">apparent sizes</a> of the moons Phobos and Deimos are sufficiently smaller than that of the Sun; thus, their partial "eclipses" of the Sun are best considered <a href="/wiki/Transit_(astronomy)" class="mw-redirect" title="Transit (astronomy)">transits</a> (see <a href="/wiki/Transit_of_Deimos_from_Mars" title="Transit of Deimos from Mars">transit of Deimos</a> and <a href="/wiki/Transit_of_Phobos_from_Mars" title="Transit of Phobos from Mars">Phobos</a> from Mars).<sup id="cite_ref-nature436_267-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nature436-267">&#91;266&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-268" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-268">&#91;267&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Transit_of_Mercury_from_Mars" title="Transit of Mercury from Mars">Transits of Mercury</a> and <a href="/wiki/Transit_of_Venus" title="Transit of Venus">Venus</a> have been observed from Mars. A <a href="/wiki/Transit_of_Earth_from_Mars" title="Transit of Earth from Mars">transit of Earth</a> will be seen from Mars on 10 November 2084.<sup id="cite_ref-jbaa93_269-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jbaa93-269">&#91;268&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Viewing">Viewing</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_-_2020_Opposition_(crop).jpg" class="image"><img alt="see caption" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Mars_-_2020_Opposition_%28crop%29.jpg/220px-Mars_-_2020_Opposition_%28crop%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="220" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Mars_-_2020_Opposition_%28crop%29.jpg/330px-Mars_-_2020_Opposition_%28crop%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Mars_-_2020_Opposition_%28crop%29.jpg/440px-Mars_-_2020_Opposition_%28crop%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="960" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mars_-_2020_Opposition_(crop).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Mars seen through an 16-inch amateur telescope, at 2020 opposition</div></div></div>
<p>The mean <a href="/wiki/Apparent_magnitude" title="Apparent magnitude">apparent magnitude</a> of Mars is +0.71 with a standard deviation of 1.05.<sup id="cite_ref-Mallama_and_Hilton_17-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mallama_and_Hilton-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Because the orbit of Mars is eccentric, the magnitude at <a href="/wiki/Opposition_(planets)" class="mw-redirect" title="Opposition (planets)">opposition</a> from the Sun can range from about −3.0 to −1.4.<sup id="cite_ref-MallamaSky_270-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MallamaSky-270">&#91;269&#93;</a></sup> The minimum brightness is magnitude +1.86 when the planet is near <a href="/wiki/Apsis" title="Apsis">aphelion</a> and in <a href="/wiki/Conjunction_(astronomy)" title="Conjunction (astronomy)">conjunction</a> with the Sun.<sup id="cite_ref-Mallama_and_Hilton_17-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mallama_and_Hilton-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> At its brightest, Mars (along with <a href="/wiki/Jupiter" title="Jupiter">Jupiter</a>) is second only to Venus in luminosity.<sup id="cite_ref-Mallama_and_Hilton_17-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mallama_and_Hilton-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Mars usually appears distinctly yellow, orange, or red. When farthest away from Earth, it is more than seven times farther away than when it is closest. Mars is usually close enough for particularly good viewing once or twice at 15-year or 17-year intervals.<sup id="cite_ref-271" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-271">&#91;270&#93;</a></sup> As Mars approaches opposition, it begins a period of <a href="/wiki/Apparent_retrograde_motion" title="Apparent retrograde motion">retrograde motion</a>, which means it will appear to move backwards in a looping curve with respect to the background stars. This retrograde motion lasts for about 72 days, and Mars reaches its peak luminosity in the middle of this interval.<sup id="cite_ref-zeilik02_272-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zeilik02-272">&#91;271&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The point at which Mars's geocentric longitude is 180° different from the Sun's is known as <a href="/wiki/Opposition_(planets)" class="mw-redirect" title="Opposition (planets)">opposition</a>, which is near the time of closest approach to Earth. The time of opposition can occur as much as 8.5 days away from the closest approach. The distance at close approach varies between about 54 and 103&#160;million&#160;km (34 and 64&#160;million&#160;mi) due to the planets' <a href="/wiki/Ellipse" title="Ellipse">elliptical</a> orbits, which causes comparable variation in <a href="/wiki/Angular_size" class="mw-redirect" title="Angular size">angular size</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Laskar2003_273-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Laskar2003-273">&#91;272&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-274" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-274">&#91;273&#93;</a></sup> The most recent Mars opposition occurred on 13 October 2020, at a distance of about 63&#160;million&#160;km (39&#160;million&#160;mi).<sup id="cite_ref-sheehan970202_275-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sheehan970202-275">&#91;274&#93;</a></sup> The average time between the successive oppositions of Mars, its <a href="/wiki/Synodic_period" class="mw-redirect" title="Synodic period">synodic period</a>, is 780 days; but the number of days between the dates of successive oppositions can range from 764 to 812.<sup id="cite_ref-Meeus2003_218-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Meeus2003-218">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Mars comes into opposition from Earth every 2.1 years. The planets come into opposition near Mars's <a href="/wiki/Perihelion" class="mw-redirect" title="Perihelion">perihelion</a> in 2003, 2018 and 2035, with the 2020 and 2033 events being particularly close to perihelic opposition.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_30-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-30">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-276" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-276">&#91;275&#93;</a></sup> Mars made its closest approach to Earth and maximum apparent brightness in nearly 60,000 years, 55,758,006&#160;km (0.37271925&#160;AU; 34,646,419&#160;mi), <a href="/wiki/Magnitude_(astronomy)" title="Magnitude (astronomy)">magnitude</a> −2.88, on 27 August 2003, at 09:51:13 UTC. This occurred when Mars was one day from opposition and about three days from its perihelion, making it particularly easy to see from Earth. The last time it came so close is estimated to have been on 12 September <a href="/wiki/Middle_Paleolithic" title="Middle Paleolithic">57,617 BC</a>, the next time being in 2287.<sup id="cite_ref-rao030822_277-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rao030822-277">&#91;276&#93;</a></sup> This record approach was only slightly closer than other recent close approaches.<sup id="cite_ref-Meeus2003_218-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Meeus2003-218">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Optical ground-based telescopes are typically limited to resolving features about 300 kilometres (190&#160;mi) across when Earth and Mars are closest because of Earth's atmosphere.<sup id="cite_ref-usra_278-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-usra-278">&#91;277&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="In_culture">In culture</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Mars_in_culture" title="Mars in culture">Mars in culture</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mars_in_fiction" title="Mars in fiction">Mars in fiction</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Planets_in_astrology#Mars" title="Planets in astrology">Planets in astrology §&#160;Mars</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg/200px-War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg" decoding="async" width="200" height="253" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg/300px-War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5a/War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg 2x" data-file-width="334" data-file-height="422" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:War-of-the-worlds-tripod.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="/wiki/The_War_of_the_Worlds" title="The War of the Worlds">The War of the Worlds</a></i> by <a href="/wiki/H._G._Wells" title="H. G. Wells">H. G. Wells</a>, 1897, depicts an <a href="/wiki/Alien_invasion" title="Alien invasion">invasion of Earth</a> by fictional Martians.</div></div></div>
<p>Mars is named after the <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Rome" title="Ancient Rome">Roman</a> <a href="/wiki/Mars_(mythology)" title="Mars (mythology)">god of war</a>. This association between Mars and war dates back at least to <a href="/wiki/Babylonian_astronomy" title="Babylonian astronomy">Babylonian astronomy</a>, in which the planet was named for the god <a href="/wiki/Nergal" title="Nergal">Nergal</a>, deity of war and destruction.<sup id="cite_ref-279" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-279">&#91;278&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-280" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-280">&#91;279&#93;</a></sup> It persisted into modern times, as exemplified by <a href="/wiki/Gustav_Holst" title="Gustav Holst">Gustav Holst</a>'s orchestral suite <i><a href="/wiki/The_Planets" title="The Planets">The Planets</a></i>, whose famous first movement labels Mars "the bringer of war".<sup id="cite_ref-281" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-281">&#91;280&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Gender_symbol" title="Gender symbol">The planet's symbol</a>, a circle with a spear pointing out to the upper right, is also used as a symbol for the male gender.<sup id="cite_ref-282" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-282">&#91;281&#93;</a></sup> The symbol dates from at latest the 11th century, though a possible predecessor has been found in the Greek <a href="/wiki/Oxyrhynchus_Papyri" title="Oxyrhynchus Papyri">Oxyrhynchus Papyri</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-jones-1999_283-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jones-1999-283">&#91;282&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The idea that Mars was populated by intelligent <a href="/wiki/Martian" class="mw-redirect" title="Martian">Martians</a> became widespread in the late 19th century. <a href="/wiki/Giovanni_Schiaparelli" title="Giovanni Schiaparelli">Schiaparelli's</a> "canali" observations combined with <a href="/wiki/Percival_Lowell" title="Percival Lowell">Percival Lowell</a>'s books on the subject put forward the standard notion of a planet that was a drying, cooling, dying world with ancient civilizations constructing irrigation works.<sup id="cite_ref-284" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-284">&#91;283&#93;</a></sup> Many other observations and proclamations by notable personalities added to what has been termed "Mars Fever".<sup id="cite_ref-fergus04_285-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fergus04-285">&#91;284&#93;</a></sup> High-resolution mapping of the surface of Mars revealed no artifacts of habitation, but pseudoscientific speculation about intelligent life on Mars still continues. Reminiscent of the <i>canali</i> observations, these speculations are based on small scale features perceived in the spacecraft images, such as "pyramids" and the "<a href="/wiki/Cydonia_(Mars)" title="Cydonia (Mars)">Face on Mars</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-286" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-286">&#91;285&#93;</a></sup> In his book <i><a href="/wiki/Cosmos_(Sagan_book)" title="Cosmos (Sagan book)">Cosmos</a>,</i> planetary astronomer <a href="/wiki/Carl_Sagan" title="Carl Sagan">Carl Sagan</a> wrote: "Mars has become a kind of mythic arena onto which we have projected our Earthly hopes and fears."<sup id="cite_ref-sagan80_52-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sagan80-52">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The depiction of Mars in fiction has been stimulated by its dramatic red color and by nineteenth-century scientific speculations that its surface conditions might support not just life but intelligent life.<sup id="cite_ref-lightman97_287-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lightman97-287">&#91;286&#93;</a></sup> This gave way to many <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> stories involving these concepts, such as <a href="/wiki/H._G._Wells" title="H. G. Wells">H. G. Wells</a>' <i><a href="/wiki/The_War_of_the_Worlds" title="The War of the Worlds">The War of the Worlds</a></i>, in which Martians seek to escape their dying planet by invading Earth, <a href="/wiki/Ray_Bradbury" title="Ray Bradbury">Ray Bradbury</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Martian_Chronicles" title="The Martian Chronicles">The Martian Chronicles</a></i>, in which human explorers accidentally destroy a Martian civilization, as well as <a href="/wiki/Edgar_Rice_Burroughs" title="Edgar Rice Burroughs">Edgar Rice Burroughs</a>' <a href="/wiki/Barsoom" title="Barsoom"><i>Barsoom</i> series</a>, <a href="/wiki/C._S._Lewis" title="C. S. Lewis">C. S. Lewis</a>' novel <i><a href="/wiki/Out_of_the_Silent_Planet" title="Out of the Silent Planet">Out of the Silent Planet</a></i> (1938),<sup id="cite_ref-sanford09_288-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sanford09-288">&#91;287&#93;</a></sup> and a number of <a href="/wiki/Robert_A._Heinlein" title="Robert A. Heinlein">Robert A. Heinlein</a> stories before the mid-sixties.<sup id="cite_ref-buker02_289-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-buker02-289">&#91;288&#93;</a></sup> Since then, depictions of Martians have also extended to animation. A comic figure of an intelligent Martian, <a href="/wiki/Marvin_the_Martian" title="Marvin the Martian">Marvin the Martian</a>, appeared in <i><a href="/wiki/Haredevil_Hare" title="Haredevil Hare">Haredevil Hare</a></i> (1948) as a character in the <a href="/wiki/Looney_Tunes" title="Looney Tunes">Looney Tunes</a> <a href="/wiki/Animated_cartoon" class="mw-redirect" title="Animated cartoon">animated cartoons</a> of <a href="/wiki/Warner_Brothers" class="mw-redirect" title="Warner Brothers">Warner Brothers</a>, and has continued as part of popular culture to the present.<sup id="cite_ref-rabkin05_290-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rabkin05-290">&#91;289&#93;</a></sup> After the <a href="/wiki/Mariner_program" title="Mariner program"><i>Mariner</i></a> and <a href="/wiki/Viking_program" title="Viking program"><i>Viking</i></a> spacecraft had returned pictures of Mars as it really is, a lifeless and canal-less world, these ideas about Mars were abandoned; for many science-fiction authors, the new discoveries initially seemed like a constraint, but eventually the post-<i>Viking</i> knowledge of Mars became itself a source of inspiration for works like <a href="/wiki/Kim_Stanley_Robinson" title="Kim Stanley Robinson">Kim Stanley Robinson</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Mars_trilogy" title="Mars trilogy"><i>Mars</i> trilogy</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-291" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-291">&#91;290&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
